Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Question for the geeks

There's no way USB can supply 5A @ 5V. That's 25W per USB port. Your
4-port USB hub will need up to 100W.

FYI, each USB port can supply 500mA (x5V = 2.5W). See
http://www.usb.org/developers/usbfaq/#pow1


FWIW, I think PCMCIA should be able to supply as much power as USB.
While I don't have the official specs, keep in mind that a PCMCIA Type
III slot can power a 1.8" hard drive (the same kind used in an iPod
maxi), these drives can consume up to 2.5W @ 5V.

It's ridiculous to think a PCMCIA Wifi use only a few mA, the radio
module needs much more than that. The typical CardBus wifi adaptor
should use 300-600mA in transmit and 20-50mA in power-saving idle.

What's more likely is that the USB adapter does draw a little more
power (maybe 20%-30%) to raise its radio output and lack power-saving
mode, but the chipset itself should consume roughly the same amount of
power as CardBus adapters.

Nick, I suggest you turning on power-saving mode in the usb wifi
driver (if it has such mode) or simply lower the radio output power
and see if it makes a difference. You can always borrow a friend's
PCMCIA card can see if there's a considerable difference in power
consumption.

- Jeff

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lycos search engine promoting screensaver that fights spam

This is all well and good, but why is Lycos trying to be my friend?

This reminds of the pop-up/under banner ads blocking programs that
have been rolled out as a 'feature' only recently by aol/netscape,
yahoo, earthlink, msn, etc, etc, et al.

Funny, I haven't had a pop-up or unwanted banner ad for YEARS before
that 'feature' got introduced by any one of these companies.

How?

By using a simple modified 'hosts' plain text file, not any sort of
special program to deal with it.

Not only that, but it has been common knowledge in the computer
industry that this is an effective way to block these unwanted banner
and pop-up/under ads, which leads me to ask why it's not included from
the get-go when installing an OS?

Why all the heel-dragging by our wonderful and benevolent corporate
powers that be?

Because in the meantime, before the end-user gets to figure this out
on their own, aol/earthlink/msn etc can collect revenue from the
advertisers, and then when things go too far they can look like a good
guy by providing the means to stop the problem that they created in
the first fucking place.

Don't get me started on spamming and spammers.

On my last dotcom.bomb job, my ex-boss had a clause in all our
website's 'terms of use' that PROMISED to sell your email address to
the highest bidder, irregardless if you were a paying customer or not.

Of course, if you tried to email my boss, you got an email back saying
that if you want to get 'white-listed' as being not a spammer, please
follow this link to a website form for you to fill out.

If this super simple method of 'white-listing,' which is used by a
spammer to eliminate spam from his in-box, were to be widely adopted
it could knock out a good 75% of the spam that people.
get.

So how come people aren't doing this yet?

Well, in my ex-bosses case, if he were to make this available to his
spammee customers he would lose his back-end spam business.

Nothing slimy about this arrangement, is there?

God bless Corporate America.

nwa

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lycos search engine promoting screensaver that fights spam

I'm impressed.

However, I'm also curious as to why wasn't Apple including a modified
'hosts' text file banner/pop-up blocker of their own, back in, say,
1996, or so, when they knew about it then, (my friend that showed me
how to do this had employee #12 on his Apple badge and he was still on
the payroll, though he didn't have to be, lucky him), and it was
already becoming a problem for people?

Apple is just doing this now?

Why the long wait?

All this stuff being brought out now to help the end user feels to me
just like it did when Ashlee Simpson got busted lip-synching, or Condi
Rice got called out at the 9.11 hearing.

Same cultural ethic at play.

Some egregious back-handed shit gets played that the end-user ends up
paying for, and the response is,

'let's just move on, shall we?'

With little, or nothing, done to remedy the situation.

I wonder how much longer people will be willing to put up with this?

nwa

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Question for the geeks

Jeff is right on.  PCMCIA cards usually have decent power
savings mode built in.   Go to system, devices, the wifi
card, properties, and look for a power savings mode.  It
may or may not have one since USB devices cater more
to the desktop crowd.

-m

On Wed, Dec 01, 2004 at 12:29:11AM -0800, Jeffrey Chan wrote:
> There's no way USB can supply 5A @ 5V. That's 25W per USB port. Your
> 4-port USB hub will need up to 100W.
> 
> FYI, each USB port can supply 500mA (x5V = 2.5W). See
> http://www.usb.org/developers/usbfaq/#pow1
> 
> 
> FWIW, I think PCMCIA should be able to supply as much power as USB.
> While I don't have the official specs, keep in mind that a PCMCIA Type
> III slot can power a 1.8" hard drive (the same kind used in an iPod
> maxi), these drives can consume up to 2.5W @ 5V.
> 
> It's ridiculous to think a PCMCIA Wifi use only a few mA, the radio
> module needs much more than that. The typical CardBus wifi adaptor
> should use 300-600mA in transmit and 20-50mA in power-saving idle.
> 
> What's more likely is that the USB adapter does draw a little more
> power (maybe 20%-30%) to raise its radio output and lack power-saving
> mode, but the chipset itself should consume roughly the same amount of
> power as CardBus adapters.
> 
> Nick, I suggest you turning on power-saving mode in the usb wifi
> driver (if it has such mode) or simply lower the radio output power
> and see if it makes a difference. You can always borrow a friend's
> PCMCIA card can see if there's a considerable difference in power
> consumption.
> 
> - Jeff
> 
> On Tue, 30 Nov 2004 16:35:11 -0800, Freak Zone!
> <freakzone@mindspring.com> wrote:
> > Definitely the USB used more power. They are designed primarily to be used
> > with a desktop system. I think the USB draws around 5 amps while the card
> > probably uses a few milliamps.
> > 
> > Ditch the USB and get a PCIMCIA card that was designed for your laptop.
> > 
> > Good luck!
> > 
> > Sean (not a geek)
> > 
> > 
> > 
> >

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Lycos search engine promoting screensaver that fights spam

On Wed, 1 Dec 2004 05:32:56 -0500, Souper Star DJ marty d, MD!
<geniusatwerk@gmail.com> wrote:
> I'm impressed.
> 
> However, I'm also curious as to why wasn't Apple including a modified
> 'hosts' text file banner/pop-up blocker of their own, back in, say,
> 1996, or so, when they knew about it then, (my friend that showed me
> how to do this had employee #12 on his Apple badge and he was still on
> the payroll, though he didn't have to be, lucky him), and it was
> already becoming a problem for people?
> 

The entire purpose of the HOSTS file is for user-specified static
domain name resolution, for their own purpose. The OS is **never**
supposed to overwrite it with their own version.

If the purpose of **your** HOSTS file is to block popups, that's
great. But that's not what it's designed for, and there are a lot of
users and admins who rely on the HOSTS file for static name
resolutions for their networks. Overwriting the HOSTS files (or adding
all kind of popup blocking domain names to them) will create a lot of
problems.

Altering the HOSTS file overrides the domain name resolution order.
It's not just for blocking popups, any TCP/IP connections to those
domain names will fail. Are you suggesting that Apple (or any OS
vendor) has the authority over IANA and the DNS infrastructure to
dictate your DNS lookups? That's a dangerous proposal, with mountains
of liabilities and security issues attached to it.

Some solutions should be implemented solely by the user because of
such liability issues.



> Apple is just doing this now?
> 

Safari's popup blocking works within the browser only, it doesn't
changes DNS resolution. Effective popup blocking within the browser is
fairly recent technology (Mozilla being the pioneer). Also remember
that browser-level popup blocker can blocks just about any popups
without prior knowledge of the legitmacy of the website and DNS name.
With HOSTS file popup blocking, you must know the DNS name you wish to
block first. It also won't work with IP # URLs.

In any case, broswer popups are HTTP and browser issues, and should be
addressed at that level, rather than at the DNS name resolution level.
Using the HOSTS file for popup blocking is a rather sledgehammer
approach.

FWIW, I'd never trust a single third-party (be it a commercial entity
or not) to maintain a blocklist of anything. It give them sweeping
censoring power to your desktop Marco, I'm surprise someone like you
aren't alrmed by the first amendment impliations of such automatic
updated blocking by a commercial entity.



- Jeff

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Reason/Orkester CD question (nrr)

If u have the CD, just copy it. It's not copy protected.

If you allowed Reason to copy FSB and Ork to the hard drive during
installation, then it shuold rarely ask you for the CD at launch.
Reinstall with the "copy sound banks to HDD" option and it'll stop
asking you for the CDs every time (but it'll still ask for it from
time to time so keep your CDs around).

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: Fwd: AUTOREPLY: handy-dandy spam white-list test request

Great idea, but how do you implement that if you don't control your
mail server you use? Import your whitelist into your mail client?
You'll still be downloading all the spam before your mail client spam
filter kicks in.

If you have too much spam in your inbox, then you need to....

1. filter it at the mail server level, ask your ISP to install
SpamAssassin or something
2. Stop giving out your email address to every website and mailing
list. Use a seperate email address for such things and keep your
private email address private (i.e. only give it out to real live
persons)
3. use a Bayesian spam filter on the desktop, they're trainable to
your personal email partterns.

Spam will never go away until mail sender header can be authenticated.
Demand your mail provider and ISP to implement DomainKeys/SPF.

- Jeff

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Music/computer stuff for sale

I'm trying to get rid of some stuff to make room for my home studio
consolidation. Make me a decent offer on something and I'll probably
take it. Feel free to forward this along to anyone you think might be
interested.

1) Rane MP-44 DJ Mixer - $1000 OBO
You know it. This is one of the finest club mixers ever created. Mine's
in near-mint condition and it's only been used twice. It's dusty from
being in storage for too long, and one of the ground thumbscrews is
missing (you can still ground 2 turntables on one line, or just order
the part from Rane). I have an SKB roto-molded rack to bundle with it if
you'd like it to be portable. The only reason I'm getting rid of it is
that I've been unable to find a decent way to mount it within my
existing setup; the connections are all on the back of the unit, so it
either needs to be rack-mounted or hung. 

2) JBL Eon (passive, pair) & QSC Amp - $500
These can either supplement an existing soundsystem as DJ monitors, or
serve as an indoor system for small spaces. I'm including a pair of
stands, but they've also got an angled edge so you can rest them on the
floor pointing upward. The QSC Amp is built like a tank. I don't have it
in front of me, but the model is an older equivalent of their new CX
line. I can go take a look at it in the attic if anyone's interested.
I'm also including two pairs of 1/4" to banana plug cables @ 20' and
50'. The whole bundle's well worth the price if you consider that the
cables themselves cost upwards of $50 apiece.

3) Roland JV-35 Synthesizer - $150 OBO
This was my first synth. I bought it in or around '95, and have since
taken great care of it. It's 5 octaves wide, 16x multitimbral and 28x
polyphonic. Inside it's got the classic Roland GS soundbank (including
the TR-606 drum patch), and you can expand its soundset with other
Roland modules. If you don't care for its synthesis, it still makes for
a great MIDI keyboard. The only drawback is that none of the sliders or
buttons is programmable. Comes with a folding stand and stretchy fabric
dust cover.

4) Novation ReMOTE 25 MIDI Controller - $225 OBO
This thing's got more MIDI-responsive controllers than you can shake a
stick at: 8 rotary potentiometers (absolute), 8 rotary encoders
(relative or "infinite"), 8 sliders, and 24 buttons arranged in sets of
8 underneath each of the controller groups. It also has 2 octaves of
semi-weighted keys, a mod/pitch joystick, and X-Y touchpad, both of
which can control 2 CCs simultaneously. This is also in mint condition;
it's less than a year old, and has seen little use in my studio since I
got the Evolution UC-33e.

5) Apple PowerMac G3 400 w/OS X 10.2 "Jaguar" - $400 OBO
This was my first Mac. I bought it around '99, and at the time it was
pretty pimp. Even now it runs OS X relatively quickly, and I was even
using it for music production until about 2 years ago. It's got 768MB or
RAM (2x256MB and 2x128MB DIMMs), a 10GB SCSI hard disk, 32x CD-ROM, and
two video cards: a 32MB ATI Radeon and 16MB ATI Rage 128. It's also got
a 100MB Zip Drive, an Apple Pro Keyboard (circa 2002--not the crappy one
that came with it), and a boxed, fully licensed copy of OS X. I've even
wiped the hard drive and prepped it for a fresh installation.

6) Hitachi 19" RasterOps monitor - $250 OBO
This thing is huge and heavy, but it sure looks great. It just takes up
way too much room in my office. It's in near-mint condition. Model
#MC7515.

7) AOC 17" Spectrum monitor - FREE!
Beat up old monitor, still works great though. I'm going to bring it to
the Salvation Army if nobody claims it. Model #7Glr.

Cheers,
--

  mailto://shawn@alterior.net
  phone://+1.415.577.3961
  http://alterior.net
  aim://shawnpallen

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Totally OT: get a free ipod.... so easy!!

Hmm.. You're comparing the battery life of iPods to.... um.... PDAs?

All the PDAs on the market now are color, at least $200 or so, and
they last for about 3-4 hours at best (you might get over 6 hrs for
listening to music if you keep the screen powered off). 1GB of flash
memory is another $70-100 (depends on what type).

I got my refurbished 15GB iPod for $199. Can't be happier. I have over
100 full-length mix CDs on it (plus 100s of 12 inches), from house to
breaks to trance to downtempo. The battery life could be better but
trust me, it last longer than my Tungsten T.

The iPod's interface is ingenius. You really have to own one to
appreciate it. The real strenth is that it integrates so perfectly
with iTunes. When you have 20-60GB of music on a portable player and
100s of GB of music your home computer, management is a real important
issue. The iTunes + iPod combo is light-years ahead of the
competition. They can copy the iPod's hardware, but none of the other
MP3 players on the market has the software to match.

Now if you don't plan on carrying that much music with you, then you
probably don't need an iPod. Just wait another year and you'll find
30% of all cell phone models have MP3 capability and flash memory slot
too.

But I really appreciate the fact that I don't have to remember copy
files to a card, or put the CDs I like in the bag, etc. When I need
music, I just pick up my iPod. All the music I want it hear is always
in it. All 200 hrs of it.


- Jeff

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Reason/Orkester CD question (nrr)

OMG, you guys are, like, totally openly discussing how to steal
software on a rave list!  That is, like, so totally grody!  I used to
be the world's biggest audio warezer, so I understand..  ..but when
something like Reason, that has all but *replaced* hardware for a lot
of people, is still sub-$500, just buy the fucker, if you have the
means.  

The more people that really support these companies, the faster they
can come out with more ill shit.  Last time I talked to a person @
Propellerhead, they told me they estimated the ratio of paying users to
warezers at 1:20.  They're still doing alright, but what if another 10%
of us ponied up?  Can you IMAGINE the amount of additional engineers/QA
folks that'd buy?  Call me crazy, but when a piece of (relatively)
cheap software turns my whole creative process on its head and
(ostensibly) changes my life, I save up and buy it.

Ahhh, fuck, I love you guys though- and if the cost of software had to
keep you from doing all the (really) cool shit you're doing, I'd rather
see you warez it than be stifled.  It's a tough question.

You're right, though, Ry- Reason 3.0 is nothing earth-shattering.  New
features are new features, but I'm not sure it really deserved a
big-buck upgrade cost and a full version number hike..  There were lots
of things people seemed to (very vocally) be waiting for more than
combis and crap.

As far as the seq being a POS.. I dunno..  It sure is easy and clear. 
I used to use it now and again when I'd tire of Logic or even PT's
relative complexity. 

Now Live 4's seq....  There is a fucking thing of beauty, if you ask
me.  Nothing but nothing can touch it, for the way I work.  I am so
damned addicted to L4 that I am constantly eyeing my home PC, dreaming
about having the time and $$$ to upgrade it to dual AMDs so I can
*really* do what I want.  It doesn't have the tweaky features at all
yet but the paradigm shift it created in my head has hardly even
settled in yet, it's so large.

Ableton pwns.  I want to move to Germany and work for them.

Blah music geek mode off, 
Cheers,

-georgeC | origami
-newstylesound recordings
-newstylesound.com
-djorigami.com
-foldedsf.com

Subject: [sfraves] Final lineup update : This Sat : Beatification of the Beat

** Lineup updated 12.2.04 **

We've added our final act to the lineup: the infamous Plateshifter, dark 
lord of the Overworld.  He's been laying low for the last few years blowing 
out his eardrums creating a crazy new techno sound that you definitely have 
not heard before.  He has sacrificed... for you!  You will think you are on 
another planet.  He is back and will be playing a late night set of his 
material, on big sound.  Definitely worth sticking around for.

Hope to see you saturday!

Full BSP below...

------------------------------------------

Freebeats, Tenderloft, Mayonnaise & DEF present...

THE BEATIFICATION OF THE BEAT
ecstatic beats for your soul and your feet
http://www.freebeats.org/beatification
Info: 415-289-6886


:::Teknosphere:::

The Attack People live PA (Abiotic Recordings, Hidden Agenda, Compound 
Records UK, Minneapolis) - http://www.abiotic.net
Deecoy (Dirty Criminals, Gigolo Records, Chicago) - 
http://www.gigolo-records.de
DJ Disconnect (DEF)
DJ Yap (Tenderloft, Freebeats, DEF)
Forest Green (Tech-On, Cloud Factory, Sister)
Gavin Varitech (Rareform Recordings, Techwest Tribe, Sac)
Plateshifter (Otherworld) - http://www.plateshifter.com


:::Breakbeat Mechanics:::

Daisy Crave (Flowbotics)
Laird (Golden Gate Recordings)
Smoove (Space Cowboys)
Sunder (Sol System)
Tonic (Mayonnaise)


:::Knob-Twiddling Nerd Alert:::

DJ M (Faultline, FutureTrax)
Graphic (Offshore, The Wave Organ)
Mr. Projectile (Merck)
Smex (Tenderloft)
Time Slips By (Trust) - http://www.timeslipsby.com

+ More TBA...


*Three rooms of beats in a secure Oakland warehouse location
*Techno, breaks, IDM, downtempo + more for dancing & chilling
*Visual stimulation by Neuralocity and Stoptime341 (http://stoptime341.com)
*Sound by Know:Audio, Gateway, and fSound
*Free fruit, water, and refreshments
*Smoothie Bar provided by Otherworld
*Flashback inducing blacklight banners by Parallaxia
*$12 at the door
*All ages, all night
*Religious experiences and epiphanies encouraged!

to think about applying for developer jobs just yet (after getting back 
from film school)
as I had been in the QA department (developing automated QA systems, but
that's here nor there) for so long (uh, 2 years, after 10 years of 
developing satellite
control systems....  of course, back then, I was in development AND qa at 
the same time)

but of course, he was a hotshot, just out of Stanford maybe 5 years ago

damn punk...  I guess my BS in CpE and MS in CS meant nothing

HR people thought the same way - every unsolicited form letter e-mail was 
generally
for a QA position.  and I could hear recruiters' brains freeze when I said 
I was looking
more for a development oriented position.

gezus...  after 20 years of IT, it's all the same damn shit

course we're all wage slaves as well (re: the EA "coal mines").  Become a 
contractor -
at least you'll get paid for every hour you work

I am *this* close to becoming a commie

doug

* The Internationale (new version/rendition)

Listen to the most festive rendition of "The
Internationale" ever, played by a Japanese band Soul
Flower Mononoke Summit.

http://montages.blogspot.com/2004/11/internationale.html


BTW, in case you don't speak Japanese or haven't sung the original with 
friends, the lyrics in English:




The Internationale


Arise, ye prisoners of
starvation!
Arise, ye wretched of the earth!
For justice thunders condemnation,
A better world's in birth.
No more, tradition's chains shall bind us,
Arise ye slaves, no more in thrall.
The earth shall rise on new foundations,
We are not nothing; we are all.

'Tis the final conflict,
Let us stand in our place.
The international working class
Shall be the human race!
'Tis the final conflict,
Let us stand in our place.
The international working class
Shall be the human race!


SECOND VERSE


We'll have no condescending saviors
To rule us from a judgment hall.
We workers ask not for their favors,
We must consult for all.
To make the thief disgorge his booty,
To free the spirit from the cell,
We must ourselves decide our duty,
We must decide and do it well!

'This the final conflict,
Let us stand in our place!.
The international working class
Shall be the human race!
'Tis the final conflict,
Let us stand in our place.
The international working class
Shall be the human race!

state to which you may belong, from all that you have held as dear as life 
itself. For this obedience is the law of our being."
   Gandhi

rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

> 1. What time do you get up?

the sun filtering through my window.

Alexander Oliver

Sucka Free.

Double Rainbow Pumpkin flava.

A Saab that's still coated in dust from Chillits.

Super-human flakeism.

Lotus.

> 16. If you could go anywhere in the world on a vacation, where would
> you go? 

*sigh*..  I'd go back to London, and then, er, miss my return flight ;)

> 17. What color is your bathroom? 

Off-white

> 18. Favorite brand of clothing? 

Whatever matches the day and my mood.  (something at least a little bit
fly though ;)

> 19. Where would you like to retire {to}?

Santa Cruz wouldn't be so bad..  Eh- cottage in the English
countryside, thanks.  :)

> 20. Favorite day of the week? 

Saturday.  It's generally all mine and it doesn't have that wistful
"shit, I've got to go to work tomorrow" sheen Sunday does.

> 21. Where did you go for your last birthday? 

Fuck, I sound pretentious- I was on vacation in London.  Coincedence, I
swear.  Enough crazy stuff happened directly afterward to help me lose
my proletarian guilt about it right-quick ;)

> 22. Where were you born? 

Santa Cruz, CA

> 23. Who do you least expect to send this back to you? 

My mom.

> 24. Person you expect to send it back first? 

Some random SFR person who copies me by accident.

> 25. What fabric detergent do you use? 

My clothes clean themselves like magic.
 
> 26. Coke or Pepsi? 

Duh, Red Bull.

> 27. Are you a morning person or a night owl? 

Hoot.

> 28. What is your shoe size? 

13.

> 29. Do you have any pets? 

My cat, Jezebel.  My brain's pretty entertaining, too. ;)

> 30. What are your least favorite traits about yourself? 

Too serious, too shy, and too damn driven.

> 34. What is your most favorite trait about yourself? 

I will soon rule the world.

Reason is a great brainstorming tool, for anyone. Especially in a
collaborative project. You don't have to worry about your frineds have
all the right VST plugins instealled, or loading all right patches,
etc.

Reason for production does leave a lot to be desired. Crappy SEQ,
nothing enough parameters in their effects....

And I fucking hate having to REXify every loop I want to put in
Dr.REX, then map the triggers to the shitty SEQ. If I use the samplers
then I'll have to time-stretch it to the right tempo.

I mean, com'on, can I just play a str8 loop? How hard is that?

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
Content-Disposition: inline
In-Reply-To: <BAY20-DAV87B9475145681B8976780BFB00@phx.gbl>
User-Agent: Mutt/1.3.28i
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Reason/Orkester CD question (nrr)



Ooo, my favorite subjects, hardware vs Software and warez!

A few things...

1.  Take a look at Spectrasonic's Stylus for good example of what
happens when people pay for software.  Stylus came on 6 CDs, so
it was nearly impossible to crack *and* get the sample data.  Now,
we have Stylus RMX, which is quite simply one of the best peices
of music software to hit the market.  And it is only a $99 dollar
upgrade for people who bougth the original Stylus.  www.spectrasonics.net

2.  Live 4.0 rocks.  Instead of fucking paying apple for a $300 upgrade
to go from Logic 6 to Logic 7, I bought Live.  Very nice.  Does not
replace Logic, but they work very good together.

3.  Hardware vs Software.  I still don't think softsynths can match
the sound quality of an Access Virus or Waldorf Q.  But even if
they could, the amount of processor overhead is huge.  Thats the
kind of thing that crashes laptops during live performances.  I
still think a good multitimberal hardware synth is a good investment.
Software can pump out MIDI data for eons and not crash, but as soon
as you drop in a few giant softsynth patches, start praying to god
your set does not blow up 1/2 way through right when the girls
are starting to get jiggy.

-troy

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Upcoming events/ISO amazing time.

Oh man i remember those days.  Right in the hight of my partying days,
i was working 4x10's at Intel, and it was Sun-Wed 5am-1pm.  There were
so many times i would drive straight from the party to work.  A few
times they were parties in Seattle so it was a 3 hour drive from the
party back to work.  Thank god on Sunday's there was only one other
person in the office and he was a total stoner and spend the whole
morning asleep, so since i was
most certainly awake those days i'd cover for him, and to pay me back
mon-wed. he'd cover my ass so i could come in 3 hours late everyday
and show up at 8am, since i was a big tweaker back then those few
hours come in very handy.  The most intense time i had was this one
time i was at a club, and i took a couple of pills, and around 1am or
so, this dude comes around with a half sheet of gel tabs, that i
picked up off him and took a few for myself, not caring that i had to
be at work in 2 hours.  4am rolls around and i was most certainly on
my way up a very intense peak.  Got my ass to work just in time for
everything to seriously start melting.  i spent the entire morning
listening to house music and staring at my desktop, which at the time
had a picture of Jim Morrison on it and he would sing every sample in
every track.  Very intense...i so cant do that anymore.  Ahhhh the
good ol reckless days back when i was invincible and had no cares in
the world.


-- 
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Upcoming events/ISO amazing time.

Yeah I was, why do you ask?  HAHAHAHAHA just kiddin.  Naw i was
working on this new product they were trying to roll out called Intel
AnswerExpress.  Some cheezy little program that users could install
and if they ever had a problem with their computer they could run this
lil app and it would pull all the information from the computer and
email it back to us and it was basically like a tech support ticketing
system, but availible to the end-user.  I was on the QA team as well
as team lead of the help desk.  It wasn't too bad since we only really
had less than 1000 customers at that time, so there was a lot of
downtime, and sitting around doing nothing.  I wonder what ever
happened with that product, i havent heard anything about it since i
left Intel.  I guess it got scrapped cause they're page isnt up
anymore.  It was a stupid program to start with.  I guess it was a
good idea, but in all reality it was just a stupid program.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr- a question (was: Upcoming events/ISO amazing time.)

Hmmmm meth monsters are hard to explain cause they're differant for
everyone really.  But bascially they're hallucinations induces by
sleep deprivation.  I used to do like 2 or 3 day stretchs and never
saw anything.  I think it was on one of my first 5 day runs that i
started to notice the "meth monsters".  When i first noticed it, i was
sitting at work (Intel) and i was looking across the office and it
looked like all the cube were on fire.  i didnt really see flames, but
you know when you look above a fire you see the heat waves, that's
what i was seeing, everything was kinda swishing back n forth.  I also
felt the "spiders" crawling under my skin, it wasnt too intense, it
would just be a few waves of a weird tinggling sensation under my
skin.  That was the first time i noticed it, each time after that it
got more intense and crazy.  There would be times i would hear my name
being called out, or phones ringing that weren't really ringing.  I
also noticed most of the time i would see people walking across the
street that weren't there, and the funny thing was it was all people
from circa 1890 or some shit, there would be people on horse and
buggy's crossing the street and women with umbrella's and the big ol
dresses and shit (my friend phatty would also have the same sort of
hallucinations).  i'd see people ducking behind garbage cans, or
crawling out of garbage cans.  One time i was staring at a sunset and
i saw this hand come stretching out from the sun and it reached out
and touched my nose.  There would be random little creatures scurring
from shadow to shadow.  One time i was driving my girlfriend home, and
i had been up for about 5 or 6 days, and it was like 4am, and i was
driving along and all of the sudden i almost slammed into the back of
a semi, so i punched my brakes and came screaching to a halt hoping to
stop in time, and once i stopped i looked around and there wasnt
anything near me for miles, i was on some rural road and there was a
McDonald's cup rolling around in the middle of the road.  I had a 5
year "addiction" to meth, so i've seen lots of crazy "meth monsters". 
That's why the freaks and addicts you come across are all twitchy and
shit, lack of sleep does horrible things to your brain, you're brain
needs to turn off occasionally to reset itself, other wise your brain
is constantly absording inputs and it gets overloaded and starts to
freak out, hence the seeing and hearing things...I spent a lot of time
trying to break it down and figure out the why's and what's and all
that.  Thats my own personal theory.

-- 
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"It's all in the reflexes"

Subject: [sfraves] Thought for Today:  If a dog was the teacher

--=====================_1509140==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed


If a dog was the teacher

If a dog was the teacher you would learn stuff like:

When loved ones come home, always run to greet them.

Never pass up the opportunity to go for a joyride.

Allow the experience of fresh air and the wind in your face to be pure
ecstasy.

When it's in your best interest, practice obedience.

Let others know when they've invaded your territory.

Take naps.

Stretch before rising.

Run, romp, and play daily.

Thrive on attention and let people touch you.

Avoid biting when a simple growl will do.

On warm days, stop to lie on your back on the grass.

On hot days, drink lots of water and lie under a shady tree.

When you're happy, dance around and wag your entire body.

No matter how often you're scolded, don't buy into the guilt thing and
pout...run right back and make friends.

Delight in the simple joy of a long walk

Eat with gusto and enthusiasm. Stop when you have had enough.

Be loyal. Never pretend to be something you're not.

If what you want lies buried, dig until you find it.

When someone is having a bad day, be silent, sit close by and nuzzle
them gently.




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Reason/Orkester CD question (nrr)

On Fri, 3 Dec 2004 10:40:14 -0800, Troy Sheets
<tsheets@atari.saturn5.com> wrote:
> 
> 
> Ooo, my favorite subjects, hardware vs Software and warez!
> 
> A few things...
> 
> 1.  Take a look at Spectrasonic's Stylus for good example of what
> happens when people pay for software.  Stylus came on 6 CDs, so
> it was nearly impossible to crack *and* get the sample data.  Now,
> we have Stylus RMX, which is quite simply one of the best peices
> of music software to hit the market.  And it is only a $99 dollar
> upgrade for people who bougth the original Stylus.  www.spectrasonics.net
> 

How it that a logical arguement? The fact that it comes on 6CDs is not
proof that it's unw4r3zable. (I can give you the torrent/ed2k links as
counter-proof  ^_^). The fact (or, more acuratly, "your opinion") that
it's good software doesn't mean it's a direct result of good sales.

Not to discount that Stylus (and Trilogy and Atmosphere) are excellent
soft synths. But that's doesn't really have anything to do with "what
happens when people pay for software".


> 2.  Live 4.0 rocks.  Instead of fucking paying apple for a $300 upgrade
> to go from Logic 6 to Logic 7, I bought Live.  Very nice.  Does not
> replace Logic, but they work very good together.
> 

$300 for an upgrade? That's ridiculous. I love Apple, but they really
milk you for everything.


> 3.  Hardware vs Software.  I still don't think softsynths can match
> the sound quality of an Access Virus or Waldorf Q.  But even if
> they could, the amount of processor overhead is huge.  Thats the
> kind of thing that crashes laptops during live performances.  I
> still think a good multitimberal hardware synth is a good investment.
> Software can pump out MIDI data for eons and not crash, but as soon
> as you drop in a few giant softsynth patches, start praying to god
> your set does not blow up 1/2 way through right when the girls
> are starting to get jiggy.
> 

I hate it when people compare hardware and software today as if
there's any significant differences under the hood. Modern hardware
synth (like Access Virus or Waldorf Q you mentioned) are all
DSP-based. They're really proprietary software synth running on
dedicated DSP hardware in a keyboard form-factor. The same prorietary
DSP software can be port to virtually any platfrom if they choose to.
There's even a Virus plugin for Lexicon PowerCore.

If you port the the Virus or the Q to a PC or Mac, they should sound
virtually the same, because the only thing different is the CPU, which
isn't going to affect the audio fidelity (well, unless your playing it
out of a Sound Blaster).

A G4/G5 or a P4 is orders of magnitude more powerful in DSP processing
than any dedicated DSP today (thanks to SIME vector instructions like
MMX and Altivec).

Reliabilty is very much the hallmark of hardware synths, but that's
because they do 1 thing and do 1 thing well. A computer is always
running a complete OS underneath (plus all your plugins). If you strip
down the OS to a minimum and run just a single program, it'll be
equally reliable. FinalScratch on the PC is a good example (because it
runs on Linux, you can install a dedicated Linux environment solely
for running FinalScratch and nothing else). Likewise, it's common
practice to install a bare OS for running nothing but Ableton Live for
performances, for stability reasons. And in these scenarios, the
computers are not very different from dedicated hardware.

The line b/w hardware and software setup is constantly blurring. You
see hardware that suppoort plugins, or has a complete GUI (like the
high-end Roland HDD multitrackers), and you'll see software that
requires dedicated hardware (like PowerCore and ProTools) or have a
closed environment (like Reason). I might even expect some software in
the future to come with its own OS (like a stripped down Linux) and
take control of your entire computer.


- Jeff

Subject: [sfraves] Blast The Speakers was So Dope lastnight!! YAY Modified!!! =)

So i had the honor of takin' out a Bay Area Scene Newbie 2 this like most
excellent Shindig lastnight.. Helllo 2Day. So Dope!!!  I mean...
seriously.. I just like planned on staying home lastnight doin' hoework
'cause I got like mondo catch up 2 do w/ my current class (YUCK.. I hate
this class).... but OK.. so opportunity came up 2 go out & well.. I
hmmm... I guess I was rather pushed in2 it then aaaah fuck it man.. I
wanted 2 Groove, so I went out.. la la la!  LoL

So yeah.. the spot was Dope... I swear man.. it was like a total treasure
hunt kinda ummm... like with the specific path you totally had 2 take 2 go
up stairs.. LoL.. it was fun!!  Walk this narrow wooden like plank to get
1/2 way upstairs.. walk through a bridgelike balcony kinda thingie, then
climb the stairs.. then go through a bumpy narrow hallway in the dark...
fun stuff man.. LoL

Music was alright!!  OK.. the 1st DJ who was like spinning down stairs was
actually some dude i met waaaaaaaaaaay back in the day @ Maratime.. LoL...
& we totally played catch up the whole night talkin' & shit... Dope!  But
this Dude... Daniel... was like playin' heeeeeeeeeella old school Hardcore
Breakbreak beats, then busted out Funky house, back 2 Break beats, a lil'
futurie this time, then back 2 house!! Yummy fuckin' set!  Upstair, if i
remember correctly, it was breakbeats also this time... then "Navaro" went
on next w/ his Trance,,, downstair, Tenchi no nonono, LMNT went on 1st
then Tenchi with their intense trance sets!!!  mmmm.. yummy!!  OK.. Nick
Nyquil went on somewhre in there!!  Loved it!!  Yummy Br3eakbeats!

OK... it was just a fun night!  Saw alota people there... So Dope!!!  YAY!!

Groovy times! Can't wait 'til the next 1... KENT... THANK U SOOOOOOOOOO
MUCH MAN!!!  & LMNT.. YAY!!  You're Dope!!!  Hey.. I was # 49 & # 54!!! I
swear!

MOSH VIDEO RE-EDITED

EMINEM





The video for EMINEM's political song MOSH has been re-edited to give it a 
fresh message following GEORGE W BUSH's Presidential election victory over 
JOHN KERRY.

The original cut of the video ended with a shot of an animated Eminem 
leading a mob to register to vote, but this has been changed now the 
election has taken place.

The video's director, IAN INABA, says, "When MTV saw it, the top brass 
there decided to put it on heavy rotation and make it the number one video 
on that week. But because (the video) had so much popularity, we had to 
figure out how to keep it going seeing that the voting thing didn't work 
out so well."

INTERSCOPE, Eminem's record label, agreed to pay for a new 50-second ending 
which now features the same mob storming the Capitol during Bush's State Of 
The Union address. This leads to a shot of DICK CHENEY suffering a heart 
attack.

Inaba admits, "There was some back-and-forth with management over whether 
this was too strong."

30/11/2004 21:57

http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/mosh%20video%20re.edited

face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."

Subject: [sfraves] Granny Has Left The Dancefloor

--=====================_1894313==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Granny Has Left The Dancefloor
to join DJ Goddess in the IAMbient Room
An obituary for Rosy Rofe
by your roving ACCESS-ALL-LEVELS reporter Fraser Clark

Former Queen of Clubs and "Dancing Granny" to Britain's Rave Generation, 
died, aged, 80, on Monday 22nd(she never much cared for Mondays :)

"I'll ask the DJ to turn the music way down low (some hope, huh?)
And you can tell your friends there with you she had to go"

During the course of writing and researching this obit, I have been 
presented with the idea that Rosy should be deified by the neo-pagan 
community, and that her charity Peacebuilders Trust should be revived.

Quite simply, Rosy Rofe was one of the highest points of light in the early 
days of underground Rave Culture, back when damn near everybody thought it 
was just about music and would be a passing fad.  Just to see her dancing 
away in that endless effortless Alexander-style of hers, a smile of pure 
physical pleasure across her face, used to hit you as a reassurance that 
what we were all doing WAS about more than music & fashion  at least it was 
also about dancing and non-ageism!

Certainly, from Megatripolis onwards, I could/would never have dreamed of 
putting on any club without her as my Hostess.  She seemed to know 
everyone, and even more knew her.  She was unquestionably a secure landmark 
and an oasis of care for many many young clubbers dancing their first steps 
beyond the Designated Motorway.  (I remember someone telling me during the 
Zippy Tour that I didn't need to DO anything any more, I just had to exist 
in order to show young people it is possible.)

Nor have I met many people who lived more in the moment than Rosy, even to 
the point where she would pop just about anything empatheogenic just like 
that, and even to the extent that she found it hard to be home, 
alone.  That must have been hard, I'm glad I was never like that, I 
positively craved some time alone during that era.

Rosy was born Dorothy Leckstein, on May 24th, 1924, slap in the middle of 
the Roaring '20s, Destiny clearly never intending her to go through life 
quietly.  The Rofe part of her name came from her husband Hussein Rofe, 
head assistant to Bapak, the spiritual leader of the Subud religion which 
swept Europe through the Psychedelic '60s.  The Rosy part (Rosanna) was 
given her by Bapak, her guru.

Though she was a great beauty, sketched by Augustus John, photographed by 
Cecil Beaton, and wined, dined and bedded across Europe, she had a very 
serious thirst for knowledge.  In her twenties, she studied the Alexander 
Technique under (I use the word advisedly) the old teacher himself, Mathias 
Alexander.  This was to give her the infinite energy that, much later in 
her life, would allow her, always, to be the only person still dancing at 
the end of the after-after-after party.

Very lucid as regards World Peace, hands-on community and all the issues of 
the day (she'd been a White Witch at one stage, and was even a member of 
their union!) she would sometimes just beam silently at you in 
clubland.  People had different ideas what was going on but the truth is 
she tripped out a lot (a taste for LSD had followed her from the '60s and 
caught up with her in the '90s) and she often told me she was actually 
watching fairies and elves climbing and playing and posing all over people 
as they talked to her :)

Subud might have been her deepest influence.  Certainly its Latehans 
(sessions where you were supposed to let it all hang out, to put it too 
crudely) encouraged her ability to let the Larger Force express Itself 
through her.

Her association with the roses that she used to make and give away or sell 
to cover her running expenses, began when Lindsay Kemp commissioned her to 
create a thousand red roses (or more?) for a staging he mounted of Genet's 
"Our Lady of the Flowers".

The fact that Rosy was born of a Russian father and a Polish mother who 
came from a long line of milliners and dyers certainly explains her love of 
dressing up and her love of colour.  It was in the DNA!  Indeed, one member 
of the family I interviewed for this obit described the family as all 
having "a great love of colour".

During the Sixties, of course, she lived a very wild life, which included 
alleged trysts with Keith Richards, John Bennett (Gurdjieff) and others too 
nefarious to mention.  For one period of her life she and Eva Bartok shared 
a Buckminster Fuller dome!  Certainly she hung out with the likes of Angie 
Bowie, and the gang around her.  She always claimed she conceived the Body 
Mind & Spirit Festival, only to have it stolen from under her by Graham 
Wilson and other hard businessmen.   If Bugsy is listening, I'm here to say 
it happens.


In the immediate aftermath of a death, I've noticed, we initially make the 
mistake of seeing the old person, the latest form which has just passed 
away.  It takes some weeks before the overall person, in its most developed 
visual form, takes its place.  I think we also vastly underestimate how 
people 'die,' move on, piece by piece, the moment of death being when the 
last piece moves on too.  At least for their last year, a person is half 
not here, that's either half the time here and half the time there or all 
the time half here half gone.  Thus, their appearance and 'living 
conditions', to which we give such insane importance, are pretty immaterial 
to those who're already and increasingly 'moved on' to another world where 
this one's but a passed dream.

In Rosy's case the talk has been of her last year when her daughter Astrid 
persuaded her up to the cold unknown depths of Carlisle and, with Rosy's 
half-agreement, discouraged all contacts from her former friends.  Just 
your old Bourgeois-Hippy divide that still splits many families, but 
classically from Rosy's generation (think Absolutely Fabulous and you're 
there)   Maybe it was hard for Rosy, maybe many things, but the point to 
bear in mind is that it doesn't matter to her now and would only have 
really mattered to half of her then :)  She was already more than half gone 
when she went North, I can vouch for that.  Whenever I hung out with her 
during the previous year she was deteriorating fairly rapidly.

I'd always get her well stoned on my visits, and then insist that she tell 
God(ess), when she got there ("it doesn't matter when, Rosy!"), how good I 
was at putting on parties ("cos they love parties up there, you know that, 
girl!") and to make sure SHe put me on the Guest List.   At first she used 
to look at me strangely, she was afraid of death and always loved the 
bright social lights.  But my insistence and playful repetition got through 
on quite a deep level, or so I felt.   She'd recognise she'd heard this 
gibberish before, but not exactly where (was it on one of Heaven's flyers?) 
and it started to crystallise in her a more optimistic picture of where she 
might be heading.  I hope so anyway  certainly she used to laugh fondly at 
it by the time she headed North.

At least get me on the½ Price Guest List, Rosy!


a l l    g o o d    t h i n g s    c o m e    t o    a   n      e   n    d
which   don't   justify     nuttin'

Subject: [sfraves] Fwd: Groovegate...for those of you  looking to get your labels out


--- Groovegate <info@groovegate.com> wrote:

---------------------------------
         
Dear club music lover,

Pitch Adjust's Digital Music Distribution service,
Groovegate, is soon ready. Starting tomorrow we will
start adding the tracks from the labels that has sent
us their music as well as the other labels that has
signed up will be able to upload their catalogues via
their browser. If all goes well, we are looking at
launching the site in the beginning of January.

Do you want to join? Want more info?

If you don't know it yet, Groovegate is a Digital
Music Distribution market place that are open both for
labels as well as unsigned artists which gives you the
ultimate experience when it comes to selling your
music online. By working closely with the Pitch Adjust
magazine, we are able to promote your music to the
highest level and this makes us stand out really well
from our competitors. We are also negotiating right
now with a coming online radio!  station were their
listeners is only presented with music from Groovegate
with direct links to buy the tracks they hear. This
will be, if negotiations is successful, yet another
added bonus to get your music heard and sold.

You can read more about the Groovegate service at
www.groovegate.com and this is also where you'll find
all documentation needed to join.

Labels that has joined already include;

** Baroque, UK (13 labels in total)
** Jaxx Records, Spain (10 labels in total)
** Night Drive Music
** Route 33
** Resin Records
** Digital Structures
** S.Sens Records
** Aardvark Records
** Planet Noise
** Younan Music


Is it legal?

Yeah Pitch Adjust will be totally legal, this is not
another Jetgroove thing. We will pay mechanical rights
as well as sending in sales reports to the copyright
assoc! iation here in Sweden called STIM. 

We at Pitch Adjust ! hope that you will find our
Groovegate distribution site interesting and that you
will join in soon... If you act now, you will find
your music on sale from day one.

More things to come!

We have now started working on some very interesting
solutions for music business use online. These tools
include;

** A store solution for Record labels and Distributors
** A online promotion tool were you send out messages,
handle feedback response sheets and mp3 promo files
via the web browser and much more
** A online tool for your complete music business with
functions like royalties, agreements, contacts, audio
and much more

If you want to be notified when these tools are
available, send a message to info@i-d-media.com and we
will add you to a special product list...

Thanks for listening and I hope to hear from you soon.

Best regards,

Patrik Sjerén
Founder
Pitch Adjust!  / Groovegate / IDMedia

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] Free License for Mackie Tracktion for PC/Mac

Mackie is giving away free license for Tracktion, their MIDI/adio
software sequencer (like Cubase). It's actually a very nice piece of
software, supports VST plugins, Ogg audio tracks, Rewire 2.0 for
integration with Reason, and a whole lot of other things. It's
resource-friendlier and easier to use than Cubase (though obviously
not as powerful).

Not sure how long the promotion's gonna last, so tell your friends.

- Jeff

OK... so like each time I've went 2 TELIC 4 an event.. something better
always happens that makes it better than the last TELIC Rave I went 2..
well.. IMO anyway... I do gotta say, Thank God that whack ass Security is
gone & there were only Groovy Cool Security working there!!

OK... so like it was Dope!  I mean... this was mainly a Trance party w/
all the DJs on the line up & yeah... it was kinda high on the foo foo
anthem metter.. LoL.. but it was... ya know.. when in Rome!

I did dance alot.. there were alota Groovy sets!!  But honestly... my
Homie Durty who broke it down w/ w. this like high energy trance that was
hella pumpin.. I was so diggin' it!  I mean.. he even mixed in some of his
own produced tracks & it was just sick!!! Ummmm... I wish i had a website
2 direct y'all 2.. well... http://www.tiggerlovesyou.com/atwr/IMG_6976.jpg
 that's Durty knob tweakin'!!!

DJ D & Aleks played this I guess like hard house/ NRG set!!  It was fun!
There was 1 DJ there who spun like 70's & 80's music.. that was fun! Oh Oh
Oh.. then there was this DJ who spun Electro!! I was sooooooooooo mondo
diggin' on that!!  Hell Yeah!

Oh yeah.. Cops came 2 try 2 shut down the party 'cause some well.. ok..
this is what I heard.. some Dude  who got kicked out called the cops &
tried 2 get the TELIC busted... Oh well.. it didn't work... after brief
chats w/ the venue owners, the cops left & literally said, "Let you party
go on as long as you want!"  Hello 2day!!  LoL  So that was kinda
intersting... Oh yeah.. i heard there was also a FIRE on 1 of the cars,
nothing like exploded from waht i was told, just alot burned plastic I
think???

Ummmmmm... oh ohoh.. so like after the last official set on the line up
ended.. i dunno who was spinning.. Wavelengh???  Anywaze... Dragnfly pops
up & spins this like hella dark proggy trance set!!  YUM!!!  I mean.. no
offense 2 like all the DJs who spun, but Dfly's set was Dark & Yummy, the
way I Like my trance!!!  Then Reclipse hops on & play this Yummy Jungle!! 
YAY!!

So yeah.. the decorations were mainly banners on the wall, this multicolor
lazer thingie, oh ohoh.. there was a balloon drop... actually 2!  LoL  The
Vibe was Groovy!!  LoL.. Hello 2day.. soooooooooo many people were there
that well.. I mean.. ok.. yeah.. I admit I have went 2 more candy raves
this past year than I like ever have, but yeah... LoL.. so like it's just
fun seein' every1 & all that!!  I'd say peak point of the shindig when I
was there was like maybe 400 people more or less....  LoL.. but yeah man..
so much fun!!!  I maean.. it's hella fun getting 2 know the kids from
BayRaves!!  LoL

OH yeah.. I dunno ifi mentioned I went there w/ my HOmie Nate
http://www.tiggerlovesyou.com/atwr/IMG_7051.jpg  & LoL.. he said 2 me when
we 1st got there, "Dude... I didn't know candy parties like this existed
anymore.. this is fuckin' CooL!"  So yeah.. this was a fun time!!!  Oh
Gosh man.. there was so much 2 do Sat night... WTF man... LoL.. well.. I
spended it the best way I knew I coulda!!  YAY

Oh.. so anywaze, I was suppse 2 ride home w/ my Homie Daniel, but after he

lei lo mo gor chow hai yeen hau lye gon jeng nei lo mo gor see fut loong
la", & like luckily finished pumping her gas & we hella got back in the
car hella quick 'cause I dunno... hella heated man!

The Asain man hella got back in his Limo & i saw him say something 2 his
driver... so as soon as we pulled out of the gas station & like go to the
freeway... next thing we knew... the limo was right behind us...

"Dina, Girl,i thought U didn't speak Chinese?" I asked her.

"I don't Oz, " she said.  "I speak Cantonese!"

"What the hell did u say to him that pissed him off?  Oh ohoh.. & when the
hella did U start speakin' Cantonesse???"

""Dude, you don't wanna know...see .. I worked part time for the American
Embassy in China as a side gig when i 1st started DJing & I had to learn &
speak Cantonese... this was years ago, but I still remember alota bad
phrases & stuff"

"Oh, OK" I said in amazement.

Anywaze, so like were' drivin' up the freeway, zoomed through that fly
thingie that goes to 80, then we got to 80. But man.. the limo was still
behind us!!  As soon as we were able to, we took an exit, made so many
turns to lose the limo, then somehow ended up by the old Bayer Factory in
Berkeley!  Hello 2Day, there was a broken down bus right there with what
looked like well... weird lookin' people and animals!  Weird!  So Dfly
parked her car by the busto try to camaflauge (sp) he car with the
commotion goin' on!  It kinda worked I guess 'cause we saw the limo like
drive by the cross street from where we were at.

So like I saw this midget like carrying a lama & I dunno.. I was sooooo
confuses!  But I asked the midget what was goin on.  He said that they're
the side show attractions to the Circus across the freeway from where they
were @... they took a wrong turn & when they tried to make a u-turn in the
area... the bus broke down... so now they were kinda stuck.  They have to
somehow get themselves & all they animals to the Circus ground in 2 hours
when the gates open!  LUckily I remembered about this outdoor underground
that happened not too liong ago & this was the exact spot we had to like
park cars, then walk to the kinda new still walking bridge to get to the
otherside..

I told all the other midgets, the lady with a beard, the manticore horse
man dude, the fat lady twins connected by their waist, and the paper thin
man where t go.  Since Dfly & I were not in the mood 2 get shot by some
crazy Chinese Mafia man... we helped!  All of us basically had to
transport all the animals to the Circus grounds!  The midgets carried the
cages of chickens, the fat lady twins carried the 3 lamas and put the 4
moneys on their backs, Dfly pushed the tank w/ the mermaid in it... I
pulled the baby elephant on a leash while holding 2 ducks in my arm.

We all trecked across the wallking Bridge to the other side of the freeway
where Frontage road is... then we walked like a quarter of a mile to the
Circus Grounds and placed everything where it needed to be!  The
ringleader saw me & Dfly helping & wondered who we were told him what
happened and he ofered us some food and asked if we wanted to be in
theCircus for a day!!  I was like Hell Yeah!!!  Dfly was all like, Well I
dunno... after 95 when I left Cirque Desoile in 96, I swore I was never
gonna be in the Circus again!"

Well, I convinced Dfly that this was for our own protection so we have to
do this!  She agreed & asked to do Trapeeze acts sinnce that's what she
was @ Cirque... turns out she tourned w/ Cirque & did alota acrobatic work
with them....  So when the show started, I got on a motorcycle and had to
ride it acroos the circus tent while it was on Fire!.. Hello 2day... well
it was fun!! Then I learned how to jump from it &jump on a trampaline
while i'm still on fire, then land in a pool of water.. it was fun!! 
Shortly after I did that.. the trapeeze artists were slowly descended from
the top of the circus tent roof thingie on their swings... then dfly
started swinging back & forth on her swing then did this tumble thingie in
the air toward the other dude on the opposite swing across from her &
grabbed his hands!  It was Dope!!!  There was like 6 of them doin' tricks
4 like 15 mintues I guess...

The Groovy thing that me & dfly were allowed to do was this really Awesome
Exit... she jumped down from the swing into the net... then from the net,
she jumped on the back of the fire motorcycle I was driving (but it wasn't
lit up now), then we drove out of the Circus!!!  LoL.. hella people
started cheering.. actually.. we had to Circle the whole tent like once,
then we drove out!  We kinda just back tracked back to where the car was
parked by the Bayer Building.. LoL.. it was kinda fun & scary 'cause that
walking bridge over 80 was kinda freak.. it wasn't that wide 4 the whole
bike so I popped a wheelie the whole time we wre on there...

So we got back to where the car was by the broken down bus...  on the hood
of Dfly's car... someone scrathed in "THIS ISN"T OVER YET BITCH! I"LL FIND
YOU!"  OK.. so like if that was written by the Chinese dude, when the hell
did he learn how 2 speak english that quick?  Hello 2day!!

So yeah.. the rest of the ride home was pretty much in silence, well, I
kinda noticed how D was still wearin' her leatard thingie from the Circus
& couldn't stop laughing @ 1 point!!  LoL... <3 U

But yeah... that's what happen this time!!!  Oh, if anyone wants free
tickets to the Circus.. oh shit.. Dina.. I left my tickets in your car!! 
When will I see U again Sweetie???

Oh... The End!!  Crazy, huh?  LoL
-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O¡ìbY {8O)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Reason/Orkester CD question (nrr)

Just a few more thangs,

--- Jeffrey Chan <goofrider@gmail.com> wrote:
> I hate it when people compare hardware and software today as if
> there's any significant differences under the hood. Modern hardware
> synth (like Access Virus or Waldorf Q you mentioned) are all
> DSP-based. They're really proprietary software synth running on
> dedicated DSP hardware in a keyboard form-factor. The same prorietary
> DSP software can be port to virtually any platfrom if they choose to.
> There's even a Virus plugin for Lexicon PowerCore.

For me, the hardware/software split comes not when comparing current
software with current ROMpler/digital synths, but with analogue gear
and older, more characterful digital stuff.  I got rid of all of my
expendable digital stuff years ago when I felt the sea change to soft
synths had made them obsolete.  What I kept was things like my 12-bit
(grungy) sampler that has analogue filters, analogue synths, my rhodes,
etc.

Not only are these archaic devices fun as hell to play, there just are
not servicable software replacements for them (yet).  Emulations, fair
stabs at them, sure- but nobody's gonna model a Rhodes that is subtlely
broken in a precious way like mine is.  Even when computer power feels
intimate and the modelling is so good that these things *could* be
emulated, who's going to make a virtual Pianet, or model my FAT
FreeBass?  Nobody, because not many people care about these magical
objects.  That, and user interface contributes in a big way to the
sounds and ideas that these objects inspire- either by the way they
play, look, feel, or even smell :)

When LinPlug makes a virtual ESQ-1, I'll feel like somebody out there
is listening (and is, perhaps, hitting the crackpipe a little too hard
;).

> If you port the the Virus or the Q to a PC or Mac, they should sound
> virtually the same, because the only thing different is the CPU,
> which
> isn't going to affect the audio fidelity (well, unless your playing
> it
> out of a Sound Blaster).

True- the Virus algorithm has been out for Pro Tools TDM for years, as
the synth and the DSP cards share the same DSP chips, and that's
apparently the same story for the Powercore.  What you still don't have
at that point is a controller with the correct labelling, that was
purpose-built for that synth and it's particular workflow.

That's not to say that I'd buy a Virus HW keyboard these days, having
the plugin, but there's something to it.

A nice step in that sort of direction, though from another angle, is
what Evolution's done with their UC-33 controller.  It's long had
overlays for programs like Live, Logic, etc which have clear labels
(and more importantly, presets to match) showing you what each knob and
button is mapped to.  Now they've updated the firmware with presets for
all of the Reason instruments, and made overlays available for each. 
So you're editing a Subtractor part, throw on that overlay and switch
presets, and BANGO, there are all the params neatly set up and labelled
for you.  Next you want to tweak a Maelstrom all to hell, switch,
swoop, BLADOW, you're there.

That's my kinda thinking.  If only it were metal, had motorized faders,
and buttons on each track.  Prob is, it'd cost a grand then.

Now, for folks that grew up with software instruments and have no soft
spot for (and, admittedly, little experience with) the classic or wierd
old stuff of the past, there's not much reason for them to get into it.
 Expensive, cantankerous, heavy, and often difficult to interface, they
can seem like an anachronism.  Once you hear them, work with them, get
your mind subtlely sheared into bits by them, though, they can have the
addictive qualities of the aforementioned crack.

Then again, I get my mind sheared to bits regularly by modern
softsynths, too- just in a different manner.  I'd be sad to be stuck
with either world.

-george C | origami
-info(at)newstylesound.com
-newstylesound recordings
-newstylesound.com
-djorigami.com
-foldedsf.com

bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

	I think someone on this list claimed not too long ago that =
Americans=20
are undertaxed compared to people in other countries. Personally I=20
think the idea that you can be "undertaxed" is ridiculous -- it's like=20=

saying you're "under-robbed" or "underenslaved." But if that remains a=20=

matter of dispute, the following article should at least be instructive=20=

in showing that American corporations face a tax rate higher than that=20=

applied to competitors in most other countries.

	Of course it will be claimed that many companies don't actually =
pay=20
anything like the full tax rate, because they apply for various tax=20
credits, choose to incorporate in low-tax states, and so on. This is=20
true, however it is also true that the various steps taken to avoid=20
higher tax bills involve a lot of time, money, effort, and decisions=20
made that would otherwise be economically unjustifiable. These things=20
also amount to a significant burden on U.S. companies. And don't forget=20=

that the corporate tax is a form of double taxation, because even after=20=

a company pays tax on its profits, individual employees, shareholders,=20=

etc., still have to pay tax again on their portions of those profits.

Peace, love & liberty,
					<<< Starchild >>>


U.S. Lags Behind Rest of World in Corporate Tax Reform
Author: Chris Edwards
Published: The Heartland Institute=A012/01/2004


Although many nations that compete economically with the United States=20=

have implemented important reforms in recent years to reduce corporate=20=

tax burdens, Congress, President George W. Bush, and Democratic=20
standard-bearer Sen. John Kerry have failed to put forth proposals for=20=

similar reforms here.

Today the U.S. has the second-highest corporate tax rate in the=20
30-nation Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).=20=

The U.S. corporate rate is 40 percent, including the 35 percent federal=20=

rate and the average state rate.

By contrast, Figure 1 (=20
http://www.heartland.org/apps/images/imgPics/BTNchartp19.3.gif ) shows=20=

the average rate in Asia, Europe, and Latin America is 30 percent or=20
less. The figure is based on data for countries listed in Table 1 (=20
http://www.heartland.org/apps/images/imgPics/BTNchartp19.2.gif ). The=20
average corporate tax rate in the OECD fell from 37.6 percent in 1996=20
to just 30.0 percent in 2004.


Since the late 1990s, many Eastern European countries have sharply=20
slashed their tax rates to attract investment. For instance:

Poland cut its tax rate from 40 to 19 percent;

Slovakia cut its rate from 29 to 19 percent;

The Czech Republic cut its rate from 39 to 28 percent;

Hungary cut its rate from 33.3 to 16 percent; and

Russia cut its rate from 35 to 24 percent.

In August, Greece announced it will cut its corporate rate from 35 to=20
25 percent, and the Netherlands announced it will cut its rate from=20
34.5 to 30 percent.


Election Failed to Address Issue Squarely

Before the November 2 general election, Bush promised to consider tax=20
reform if he won re-election, but he did not reveal a plan for the=20
corporate tax. He is allowing to expire a pro-growth tax provision that=20=

allows firms to deduct, or "expense," half the cost of qualified=20
capital investments.

Bush's challenger for president, Sen. John Kerry (D-MA), addressed the=20=

tax rules on foreign investment during the campaign, noting in speeches=20=

and campaign literature that the rules are "almost completely broken"=20
and acknowledging that other nations have corporate taxes that average=20=

one-third lower than those of the U.S.

Kerry's solutions, however, probably would have done more harm than=20
good, as a closer look suggests.


Damaging Corporate Tax Plan

The Kerry plan would have cut the U.S. corporate tax rate of 35 percent=20=

by 1.75 percentage points. To fund that small cut, however, Kerry=20
proposed to increase taxes on foreign subsidiaries of U.S. firms. Under=20=

current rules, the regular business profits of subsidiaries are not=20
taxed until repatriated to the United States.

For example, most of the 30 nations in the OECD, of which the United=20
States is a member, have "territorial" tax systems that generally do=20
not tax foreign business profits at all. The Kerry plan would have=20
broken from those norms by immediately taxing subsidiaries of U.S.=20
firms on their sales to other countries.

For example, a U.S. electronics firm selling goods from its Taiwanese=20
subsidiary to consumers in Japan would have faced a new U.S. tax=20
burden, and a relatively punitive one.

If Kerry's rules were to be enacted, U.S. companies would lose market=20
share to foreign competitors with lower tax costs, and some=20
subsidiaries would be sold to foreign companies. As their global sales=20=

declined, many of those firms would downsize their U.S. operations,=20
such as research, marketing, and management personnel. Some U.S. firms=20=

would move their headquarters to more tax-friendly countries. Others=20
would be taken over by foreign companies. All of those effects would=20
probably cost U.S. jobs.

Kerry's plan and others like it assume foreign subsidiaries of U.S.=20
firms hurt the U.S. economy. In fact, however, they mainly complement=20
U.S. production--for example, by being a primary conduit through which=20=

U.S. goods are exported abroad. By damaging the competitiveness of=20
foreign subsidiaries of U.S firms, the Kerry plan would impair=20
U.S.-based activities that depend on expanded foreign business=20
opportunities.


Tax Cuts Likely to Shift International Investment

Cuts in corporate tax rates probably will continue overseas, because of=20=

the benefits countries gain from attracting foreign investment. As much=20=

as $1 trillion of direct investment crosses international borders each=20=

year, and research shows those flows are increasingly sensitive to=20
corporate taxes.

In contrast to this global economic trend, U.S. policy rests on the=20
assumption that America can have high growth and good jobs without a=20
competitive tax climate. But many economists contend our complex and=20
costly corporate tax system will have an increasingly negative effect=20
on U.S. productivity, wages, and growth and will create a breeding=20
ground for further Enron-style tax scandals.

Chris Edwards (cedwards@cato.org ) is director of tax policy studies=20
for the Cato Institute.


THE HEARTLAND INSTITUTE
19 South LaSalle Street #903
Chicago, IL 60603
phone 312/377-4000 =B7 fax 312/377-5000
http://www.heartland.org=20=

--Apple-Mail-30--487197486--

From: Starchild <sfdreamer@earthlink.net>
In-Reply-To: <20041206232403.GE944@hubble>
Message-Id: <4965E406-4821-11D9-ADEB-003065DA480A@earthlink.net>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) U.S. Lags Behind Rest of World in Corporate Tax Reform

On Monday, December 6, 2004, at 03:24  PM, shawn allen wrote:

> quoth Starchild:
>> I think someone on this list claimed not too long ago that Americans
>> are undertaxed compared to people in other countries. Personally I
>> think the idea that you can be "undertaxed" is ridiculous -- it's like
>> saying you're "under-robbed" or "underenslaved."
>
> Whatever you say. If you don't like paying taxes, then don't take
> advantage of anything they pay for.

	That sounds a lot like "America -- love it or leave it!" You obviously 
dislike corporations. Are you going to stop using their products? For 
me the issue is not that I don't like paying taxes personally, although 
I don't -- it's that I know taxation is hurting people. I would gladly 
pay more taxes myself in exchange for having tax rates on people in 
general lowered.

>> But if that remains a matter of dispute, the following article should
>> at least be instructive in showing that American corporations face a
>> tax rate higher than that applied to competitors in most other
>> countries.
>
> And despite this tremendous barrier to success, American corporations
> make TONS more money than companies in any other country. Over the last
> decade, the S&P 500 has averaged earnings growth of 13.5%, more than
> double GDP. Boo-hoo, those poor overpaid executives, rich boardmembers
> and fat-cat stockholders. Good thing we've got thinktanks funded by
> (guess who?) US corporations to unmask these horrible attrocities!
>
> *barf*.

	I happen to agree that most executives and board members are overpaid. 
But taxing corporations does nothing to solve this problem. 
Shareholders are *not* "overpaid." They are not "paid" at all; how much 
money they make is a market function, not a management decision as in 
the case of executive pay. Anyone can buy stock. It's not some kind of 
elitist club. As of 2002, 49.5% of Americans owned stock (see 
http://www.sptimes.com/2002/09/27/Business/More_Americans_invest.shtml 
), roughly the same as the percentage of voters who voted for John 
Kerry a few weeks ago. Many more working people who do not own stock 
directly are indirect shareholders through pension funds. These 
millions of people benefit when corporate stock values increase, and 
are hurt when those companies lose money. Even people who own no stock 
directly or indirectly are affected by the economic health of the 
business world. Remember it was the stock market crash in 1929 that 
brought on the Great Depression.

	There are certainly valid questions about whether corporations should 
exist as legal entities, have limited liability, and be treated as 
persons under the law. Not to mention the problem of government 
subsidizing and favoring particular companies. But that is primarily a 
failure of government, not a failure of corporations. After all, it is 
government that sets the rules. Are corporations to blame for accepting 
handouts, or seeking to influence the political process in accord with 
their own economic benefit? To some degree yes, but then unions, 
nonprofits, and all kinds of other special interests are similarly 
guilty of lobbying for favors and trying to get the rules shaped to 
their own benefit. The root problem is that government has acquired so 
much money and power that it attracts all kinds of people and groups 
seeking financial and political gain at the expense of the taxpayers.

	Again, however, a high corporate tax rate does nothing whatsoever to 
address this problem. Not only does it do nothing, but as explained 
above, it amounts to yet another ripoff of the taxpayers. And the 
higher the tax, the greater the economic pain, not just on executives 
or the roughly half of Americans who own stock, but on society as a 
whole. Who suffered most during the Depression? It wasn't the wealthy.

Peace, love & liberty,
					<<< Starchild >>>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) U.S. Lags Behind Rest of World in Corporate Tax Reform

quoth Starchild:
> On Monday, December 6, 2004, at 03:24  PM, shawn allen wrote:
> >Whatever you say. If you don't like paying taxes, then don't take
> >advantage of anything they pay for.
> 
> That sounds a lot like "America -- love it or leave it!"

What a fantastically myopic interpretation. Given that Americans pay
substantially less in taxes than the rest of the world, it wouldn't
really make sense to leave because you feel that you're overtaxed. I
meant exactly what I wrote, and I'm not going to bother phrasing it
differently because I've made the same point on so many previous
occasions, in direct response to your self-righteous Libertarian
propaganda. Obviously you're a lost cause, but I think that everyone
else reading this is astute enough to understand it.

> You obviously dislike corporations. Are you going to stop using their
> products?

I already have. Whenever possible, I avoid purchasing products from big
corporations. Alas, there are few products that haven't been
monopolized, their production off-shored, their packaging expanded, and
their utility and reliability reduced--all at the hands of corporations
with nothing but their own short-term gains in mind.

It's a waste of my time to refute everything else you've written because
I've stated my position so many times already. For future reference,
check the archives if you want a response. I'm done arguing this idiotic
corporate worship.

Toodles,

Definitely the Evolution UC-33e. It even comes with overlays for most of
the Reason instruments.

Get that and any of the cheap 2-octave MIDI keyboards out there and
you're golden.

Not that I know of.

From: John B <SvnLyrBrto@yahoo.com>

X-Mailer: Apple Mail (2.619)
