> hardcore. I feel like throwing things at DJ's who play this shit and
> think they're hardcore. Next time i hear this at a party i'm gonna
> puke all over the record the DJ is currently playing. I'm not even
> really a big fan or current hardcore, breakcore, noisecore whatever
> the fuck it is called now. The hardcore i like is the old skool shit
> like from the early 90's, like DJ Dan and Ron D. Core used to
> spin...kinda ravey, techno-y with porn samples and heavy metal guitars
> and shit, now that's hardcore, and it's music too, too much hardcore
> now a days just sounds like noise. I dont get how people can say they
> spin it, most of it's not even broken up in to the standard 32 beats,
> and if it is, it changes up so freakin often you cant tell anyway, you
> can mix at any point and if you're skilled enough to at least match
> the beat no one would know if you fucked up or not cause it all just
> sounds like painful noise. i think Ron D. Cores medical mayhem or
> whatever it was called (released back in 97 or so) was the last of the
> good hardcore, after that i couldnt stand to listen to it, it all
> sounded the same and had no real groove to it, just felt like being
> hit in the head with a baseball bat over and over again.  This crap is
> like NRG only lamer...at least NRG can sound kinda dark and evil, this
> is like the the Emo of the electronica genre.  I'm like all hardcore,
> but i have feelings too.  what the hell is up with that, you're either
> punk rock/hardcore, or you have feelings...one or the other, those 2
> dont mix, i'm sorry and if you think they do then you're just a lame
> as the music.  as the infamous Mugatu would say "I feel like i'm
> taking crazy pills."
> 
> 
>

--- Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:

> Blues Singer-Guitarist Son Seals Dies at 62
> 
> 2 hours, 10 minutes ago
> 
> 
> By Chris Morris
> 
> LOS ANGELES (Hollywood Reporter) - Blues
> singer-guitarist Son Seals, one of 
> the most distinctive voices to emerge in the genre
> during the 1970s, died 
> Monday in Chicago of complications from diabetes. He
> was 62.
> 
> Seals helped establish Chicago-based Alligator
> Records as the era's premier 
> blues label with a run of albums featuring his tough
> songs, brooding vocals 
> and spikey guitar work. He won three W.C. Handy
> Blues Awards, and received 
> a Grammy Award nomination in 1980 for his work on
> the live compilation 
> "Blues Deluxe."
> 
> Born in Osceola, Ark., Seals learned guitar from his
> father, a former 
> minstrel show performer and juke joint operator. He
> initially established 
> himself professionally as a drummer, working with
> guitarist Earl Hooker and 
> appearing behind Albert King on the 1968 Stax album
> "Live Wire/Blues Power."
> 
> Seals moved to Chicago in 1971 and began fronting
> his own groups on the 
> city's South Side. Signed to Alligator, he made an
> immediate impression 
> with his impassioned 1973 debut "The Son Seals Blues
> Band." After the 
> release of its 1977 sequel "Midnight Son," the New
> York Times called Seals 
> "the most exciting young blues guitarist and singer
> in years."
> 
> Seals had a tempestuous relationship with Alligator
> and its founder-owner 
> Bruce Iglauer, who also managed him; he departed the
> label in the mid-'80s, 
> but returned to the fold in the '90s. His last album
> "Lettin' Go" was cut 
> for Telarc in 2000.
> 
> He toured widely, despite the loss of a leg to
> diabetes. Late in his career 
> he opened several shows for the jam band Phish, who
> covered his song "Funky 
> Bitch."
> 
> Seals is survived by his sister Katherine Sims and
> 14 children.
> 
> Reuters/Hollywood Reporter
> 
> 
> 
> 
> Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
> 
> House Music 101: 
>
http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm
> 
> 
> "The government, which was designed for the people,
> has got into the hands 
> of the bosses and their employers, the special
> interests.  An invisible 
> empire has been set up above the forms of
> democracy."
> -Woodrow Wilson
> 
> "Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one
> starved man, the look 
> on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope
> that you might have 
> bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself. 
> For that look on his 
> face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of
> bread, you might be 
> willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a
> little, even."
> -Daniel Berrigan
> 
> "Music is prophecy, its style and economic
> organization are ahead of the 
> rest of society. It makes audible the new world that
> will gradually become 
> visible."
> -Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"
> 
> 
>

fun at both. Although, OW does do things ten billion times better, Modified
does small undergrounds pretty well (despite the overabundance of
teenyboppers).

like sick ass pounding techno & other beats, and no matter how much they
advertise, will still be ten times more "underground" than anything I have
yet to experience in the Bay Area.

Hi all, 

It's been two months since we have written anything to this list, and I'll bet you missed it, right? A giant whole in your life? Ok, whatever.  

Here's a bit of news.

skylab2000 will be playing live on New Years Eve in Cleveland. It's a two day party for the price of one ticket and we are playing night one, which is actual New Years Eve. I think it's gonna be the biggest thing in the midwest, so even if you are accoss the country like I am, it could be a fun weekend trip.

Also, I hope some of you have gotten a copy of Christmas Regrooved (Amazon, Borders etc), since there's a dark breaky skylab2000 remix of a Christmas song on there.

Here's details of the New Years event: (flyer online at http://pimpshosandlimos.i8.com/pimpshoslimos.htm) 

Hope to see some of you there!

Boomerang beats, and no rapping (praise Allah.)  
Made from 100% Recycled Post-Consumer samples. 
Junkyard and break beats embracing  futuristic
escapism, in recognition that the Present is usually
laughable (on a good day).   4 originals and 1 remix. 
Ill probably include some older stuff too.

1. READY TO GO:   B-boy baddass pops the wrong pill.  
Interesting samples:  The Greaseman,  Eazy-E  & NWA,
Dr. Dre, US3, Scary Movie, Dead Man on Campus, Mr.
Deeds,  The Heist. 

2. WANDERERS: 	Outer-space escapism supported by the
poetics of Carl Sagan. A vision of the human future
in space.

3. YOUR A IDIOT: 	Ever feel like your a idiot?  Me to.
Interesting samples:  Joe Frank, Beastie Boys, Friday,
Ghost World, Full Metal Jacket, Macarthur Park, George
B., Zoolander, Scary Movie, The Score.  

4. AYAHUASCA: 	Evolution and the human riddle.  
Interesting samples:  Carl Sagan, Frank Herbert,
Dopamine

5. BUCEPHALUS BOUNCING BALL  unauthorized remix.   The
Aphex Twin song is a breath-taking mess of jungle
music fallen to beautiful technological catastrophe.  
I decided to balance the dissonance by adding the
popular theme of human/robot sex. 
Interesting samples:  Isaac Asimov,  George Herbert,
Kraftwerk,  Styx, Carl Sagan, Mike Patton (faith no
more), Gregorys Girl, I Robot, Artificial
Intelligence, Alien Hunter, the Banger Sisters, Total
Eclipse,  the Heist.

From: georgeC | origami <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
To: Nick Sideshow <nick.sideshow@gmail.com>, SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
In-Reply-To: <47bb6a3004122210367b8c8969@mail.gmail.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0

Subject: Re: [sfraves] BSP: Fitter Happier [modified new years]

Eh, every scene has its clashes in attitudes and rifts over things like
this.  Some folks here on SFR are champion shit-stirrers, but hey, even
tiffs like this raise awareness about *both* parties (no such thing as
bad publicity, etc).

The breakdown:

OW/FnF = Old-school raver types that throw infrequent but generally
breathtaking parties with varied lineups.  Musically, the stylistic net
is cast wide across the electronic music world.  There are core folks
that play regularly but pains are taken to get enough little-seen
national/international talent in to balance that. Partygoers to their
events range from candy kids to the oldest of the old guard.  They get
their pick of the venues due to respect and establishment.  Every
little detail is labored over and it shows.  Some very new ravers may
find the social scene somewhat difficult to penetrate, if only due to
differences in viewpoint and the sometimes decades-long friendships
involved.

Modified = New-school ravers that throw parties often, with a core
group of performers that does not change much from party to party.  The
music seems to center around trance, hardcore, and d&b, but with
departures from that formula here and there (who expected Andy W and
Chris Jackson that one time?).  Partygoers are generally teenagers or
early-20s folks, and a few older people checking out the scene.  The
parties are thrown quick and dirty in whatever the new warehouse or
renegade venue is.  Decorations are minimal, security is almost
nonexistant.  However, the parties often go off, everybody has fun, and
the atmosphere is relaxed.  Also, the relatively low production values
mean that the crew can throw more parties, which, to some, is a good
thing.

Both crews throw raves that are a lot of fun (I've been to scads of the
former and a few of the latter)..  You're looking at two different
viewpoints, and two very different musical leanings.  If you want a NYE
party that offers a total audio/visual experience and top-shelf talent,
come to OW.  If you want something a little more intimate with a
younger crowd and faster music, go to Modified.  

Even though I align myself more closely with the OW/FnF aesthetic, I
appreciate that people are throwing parties outside that sphere and
doing it their own way.  As long as people are having fun and expanding
their horizons a bit I'm all for it.  I'd sure rather see a 16-year-old
at a scrappy warehouse party than at some kind of mega massive!

Cheers,
-georgeC | origami
-newstylesound.com
-newstylesound recordings

georgeC | origami <newstylesound@yahoo.com> wrote:
Eh, every scene has its clashes in attitudes and rifts over things like
this. Some folks here on SFR are champion shit-stirrers, but hey, even
tiffs like this raise awareness about *both* parties (no such thing as
bad publicity, etc).

The breakdown:

OW/FnF = New-school ravers that throw parties often, with a core
group of performers that does not change much from party to party.  The
music seems to center around trance, hardcore, and d&b, but with
departures from that formula here and there (who expected Andy W and
Chris Jackson that one time?).  Partygoers are generally teenagers or
early-20s folks, and a few older people checking out the scene.  The
parties are thrown quick and dirty in whatever the new warehouse or
renegade venue is.  Decorations are minimal, security is almost
nonexistant.  However, the parties often go off, everybody has fun, and
the atmosphere is relaxed.  Also, the relatively low production values
mean that the crew can throw more parties, which, to some, is a good
thing.


Modified = Old-school raver types that throw infrequent but generally
breathtaking parties with varied lineups.  Musically, the stylistic net
is cast wide across the electronic music world.  There are core folks
that play regularly but pains are taken to get enough little-seen
national/international talent in to balance that. Partygoers to their
events range from candy kids to the oldest of the old guard.  They get
their pick of the venues due to respect and establishment.  Every
little detail is labored over and it shows.  Some very new ravers may
find the social scene somewhat difficult to penetrate, if only due to
differences in viewpoint and the sometimes decades-long friendships
involved.

Both crews throw raves that are a lot of fun (I've been to scads of the
former and a few of the latter).. You're looking at two different
viewpoints, and two very different musical leanings. If you want a NYE
party that offers a total audio/visual experience and top-shelf talent,
come to OW. If you want something a little more intimate with a
younger crowd and faster music, go to Modified. 

Even though I align myself more closely with the OW/FnF aesthetic, I
appreciate that people are throwing parties outside that sphere and
doing it their own way. As long as people are having fun and expanding
their horizons a bit I'm all for it. I'd sure rather see a 16-year-old
at a scrappy warehouse party than at some kind of mega massive!

Cheers,
-georgeC | origami
-newstylesound.com
-newstylesound recordings

back in 96-98 we never charged money for them cause of just that,

and someone to provide sound for free (it's your sound system so no
charge there), You're DJ's are basically you, and some "friends" so

love of the music and the scene right?  Are you collecting money to

known many other kids in this scene for a very long time, I love meeting new 
people as well, I love it!  We are like a family, this has been my social 
group for the past almost 9 years now.  If you find that we are too clicky, 
you have not met me and my friends.
2 cents/plur/
see you all on the dance floor in my vintage raver clothes lol
Danny



"What I am against is quotas. I am against hard quotas, quotas they 
basically delineate based upon whatever. However they delineate, quotas, I 
think, vulcanize society. So I don't know how that fits into what everybody 
else is saying, their relative positions, but that's my position." George W. 
Bush (our president)

At 01:43 PM 12/22/2004, Jonas R. wrote:

>i haven't seen these kinds of posts since the election.
>
>let's bring politics back.
>
>we've already got the politics of promoting happening full force.

Indeed, Jonas :-)  Politics, I guess, is a relative thingy.

There are many fine NYE parties out there this year.    I think both crews, 
however, are worthy of high respect.  Longevity has nothing to do with 
it.  We should all cherish those who keep our dwindling underground scene 
alive IMO.

I'm determined to stay in San Francisco this year so I'm out of this East 
Bay ug drama.  So many worthy choices in the city :  an invite only 
underground I attended last year and loved;  opening the new year with true 
skool at the gingerbread warehouse;  dancing to the Wicked crew on Mason 
Street;  Tantra at SOMARTS;  Raindance and 13 Moontribe with the Mystic 
Family Circus at Cell Space;  the FOOL warehouse party with Honey 
Dijon...and these are on my short list.

I'll be taking the N-Judah party train in so I'll stop in at as many 
parties as I can walk/hitch to :-)

Love,

Apollo

"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier, Modified, OW.



I have massive respect for Otherworld and FnF.

I'd like to start off with that. One of the best party experiences I've ever had
was at OW, and FnF is a cornerstone of the SF scene.

Now. Raves are dynamic. They thrive off of change. Raving dies with stasis,
because raves are about a celebration of -now-. And now is always different than
a minute ago. :) Also, raves are about youth. When raves are no longer about
dynamism and youth and energy and drugs and right now they stop being raves.

For the rave scene to survive, it needs to remain dynamic. A lot of people like
to talk shit about the 'new kids', these gacked out candy-wearing druggies...
when they were the same way back in 1995. ;) Maybe what I'm trying to
communicate here is -- somebody said 'we're adults - we've put away our toys' in
the mass of this conversation. Raves are about toys. :) Not about being adults.

Modified is the only hope of the 2nd rave generation. You compare them with,
say, the other spots you find youth -- coolworld. skills. the dungeon (sorry,
jared, but fuck that place is scary). Support those kids. They're trying to save
the new school.

I'm not going anywhere for NYE. I'll be holed up in the countryside frying away
the last couple hours of a shitawful year, far away from any respective
geriatravers or kiddies. Maybe when 1201 rolls across PST I'll have some kind of
wonderful moment of spontaneous gnosis. If I do, I promise to communicate it to
you gents.

<3

Sean

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

party itself.

event accomodating all ages, etc.  but these are clear facts,
not shit-talking.

- ryan started in on the trance when you talked shit about OW
having trance.

i think most of the shit talking has been about *you*, not the
party.  i talked shit on myself, because if i'm going to sling
it around, i'm sure as hell am able to take it, too.

and i don't see how everyone's representing OW.  the posts i've
seen say that they're preferring to go to OW.

i don't see the attacks on modified.  i do, however, see people
reacting to your name-calling, accusations, bigotry,
shit-talking, and various threats (veiled or blatant).  if you
can dish it out, then you should be prepared to take it.  

it's pretty simple.  you can't expect to stir the pot of shit
and have nothing happen.  ryan's the king of shit stirring. 
but he can take it, and doesn't apologize to the list when the
flames start flying and expect everyone to calm down.  shit's
stirred.  he stirred it.  he deals with it.

anyway, it's really no big deal.  it's only SFR.  who cares if
you threw up or (didn't) piss yourself?  i sure as hell don't. 
at one time people started in on some shit that i was gay. 
whatever.  so i go around and tell people my nickname is "teh
geigh".  people can think whatever they want.

X-Spam-Rating: localhost.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier, Modified, OW.

Thank you Sean for posting a lot of what I wanted to say.

In any case, I'm still sickened by the exchange I read today on SFR. And 
I still have a lot more to add to this....

I've had a number of conversations off-list due to this thread and feel a 
few issues need to be checked.

Preface: below I will be referencing 'old-school' & 'new-school' but more 
than that you are all "family" in my eyes. I only make the distinction 
to delineate where I think the conflict arises........

1) This is just a party, and "New Years"...everyone and their mom is 
throwing a party. 
Parties of every flavor, style, and size are happening. Everybody is 
coming out, and all parties can rock-out and co-exist together. There's 
certainly not room (or flavor) for only *one* party to go off this year! 
Plenty of room for all parties to go off the chain!

2) This whole flame was never about Modified vs. OW.
>From what I could gather, the vast majority seriously involved with either 
party wasn't privy to the flame-fest. The crews throwing both these 
parties are oblivious (up till now). Although, attendees are excited, it's NEW 
YEARS!...people are cheerleaders for their event of choice and that's where
the flame started. And reality check....this is about a person(s)-to-person(s)
flame. No crews involved...no animosity whatsoever.

3) Posting private email is bad. But I have talked to mike/ow, and it was 
done out of desperation because he didn't understand what was happening. 
>From our perspective, people were joking around and next a serious threat 
surfaced.

4) Old schoolers need to set an example!
Yeah, you motherfuckers on this list! 
Yeah I'm talking to you ;-)
On SFR we are sarcastic bastards, but it has come to my attention that 
our community is read and referenced on-the-outside. "So what?!?" you may 
ask, but the reality is, aside from having light-hearted jabs of 
exchange, what we say impacts how our community is perceived.

I have witnessed us talk shit about candy-ravers, and trance, but...(and I 
don't care what you say)...many of us went through the experience. And 
now, being jaded, doesn't make us any better, or above anyone.

I understand sfr has become a meeting place for us old 
folks, but in our discussion has it ever occurred that our statements are 
offensive? slandering? or at least distancing?

Perhaps not, but I would bet that's how it comes off. And I don't buy the 
argument that it's 'their' problem. It's *our* problem, because the people 
that we are dissing are the very people that will support and define the 
scene that we've committed our lives to thus far. In my opinion the recent 
active old-school scene has done a piss-poor job of embracing the next 
generation. We seem to be really good at criticizing, but not good at 
producing for our future....at all.

5) New-schoolers should understand that old-schoolers are 
self-deprecating and sarcastic.
What I've gathered is that what the old folks consider as playful banter, 
the younger kids view as slander or 'hating' (god I hate that word ;-)

The one thing I've learned in my overall career of throwing parties is to 
not take myself so seriously. I think other older people learned that too. 
In my early days if you talked shit I would have daggers in my eyes. Now I 
could care less about *anything* really, as long as the party was well put 
together, and I worked my tail off in the effort, and everyone had fun!!

6) Old school wants the New school to rock!
The end goal for everyone to thrive and prosper. I get my kicks from 
seeing other people being blown away from what our scene has to offer. I 
like people coming up and asking me what I'm doing tweaking buttons and 
knobs on a pile of gear. Perhaps part of the problem is those of us with 
resources (multiple sound systems, giant lasers, 10 video projectors, 
or just good advice) are not approachable for their efforts.

Ultimately, seeing this recent conflict makes me a bit ill. I hope 
everyone can see the shit-talking for what is is, and snap up, and 
support all positive efforts for our scene.

:-P

-terry

------------------------------------------
terry estioko     | terry@hyperreal.org
SFRaves moderator | http://www.sfraves.org

> I have massive respect for Otherworld and FnF.
>
> I'd like to start off with that. One of the best party experiences I've ever had
> was at OW, and FnF is a cornerstone of the SF scene.
>
> Now. Raves are dynamic. They thrive off of change. Raving dies with stasis,
> because raves are about a celebration of -now-. And now is always different than
> a minute ago. :) Also, raves are about youth. When raves are no longer about
> dynamism and youth and energy and drugs and right now they stop being raves.
>
> For the rave scene to survive, it needs to remain dynamic. A lot of people like
> to talk shit about the 'new kids', these gacked out candy-wearing druggies...
> when they were the same way back in 1995. ;) Maybe what I'm trying to
> communicate here is -- somebody said 'we're adults - we've put away our toys' in
> the mass of this conversation. Raves are about toys. :) Not about being adults.
>
> Modified is the only hope of the 2nd rave generation. You compare them with,
> say, the other spots you find youth -- coolworld. skills. the dungeon (sorry,
> jared, but fuck that place is scary). Support those kids. They're trying to save
> the new school.
>
> I'm not going anywhere for NYE. I'll be holed up in the countryside frying away
> the last couple hours of a shitawful year, far away from any respective
> geriatravers or kiddies. Maybe when 1201 rolls across PST I'll have some kind of
> wonderful moment of spontaneous gnosis. If I do, I promise to communicate it to
> you gents.
>
> <3
>
> Sean
>
> ---------------------------------------------------------------------
> To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
>

Subject: [sfraves] Now = Let's ring in the New Year with some P.L.U.R. Was - RE: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier, Modified, OW.

!!!!!!! THANK YOU !!!!!!!

!!!!!!! THANK YOU !!!!!!!

!!!!!!! THANK YOU !!!!!!!

Terry, for putting some much needed insight and sense into chaos! Personally
I would like to consider myself new-skool and old-skool. 

In my humble opinion, There is always so much to learn from each side of the
spectrum! I learn more everyday from my daughter and she is only 3 years
old..... and everyday she learns more from me........... The cycle never
ends!

P. = PeAcE 

L. = LoVe

U. = UnItY --- That means uniting the young and the old together as one!

R. = ReSpEcT --- Something that was obviously lost sight of over the past
thread war

Personally I don't listen to others when they say P.L.U.R. is dead, give it
up....... It's those who tell me this that I feel need it the most ;-)

It only takes a bad person to put another down, it only takes a good person
to build someone up! 

Take care and P.L.U.R. everyone,

And to all who need a little re-/education Osby will be starting P.L.U.R.
University. Enrolment is always open! The only cost of admission is Love ;-)

Matt





-----Original Message-----
From: Terry Estioko [mailto:terry@hyperreal.org] 
Sent: Thursday, December 23, 2004 2:26 AM
To: srg@pdx.edu
Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier, Modified, OW.

Thank you Sean for posting a lot of what I wanted to say.

In any case, I'm still sickened by the exchange I read today on SFR. And 
I still have a lot more to add to this....

I've had a number of conversations off-list due to this thread and feel a 
few issues need to be checked.

Preface: below I will be referencing 'old-school' & 'new-school' but more 
than that you are all "family" in my eyes. I only make the distinction 
to delineate where I think the conflict arises........

1) This is just a party, and "New Years"...everyone and their mom is 
throwing a party. 
Parties of every flavor, style, and size are happening. Everybody is 
coming out, and all parties can rock-out and co-exist together. There's 
certainly not room (or flavor) for only *one* party to go off this year! 
Plenty of room for all parties to go off the chain!

2) This whole flame was never about Modified vs. OW.
>From what I could gather, the vast majority seriously involved with either 
party wasn't privy to the flame-fest. The crews throwing both these 
parties are oblivious (up till now). Although, attendees are excited, it's
NEW 
YEARS!...people are cheerleaders for their event of choice and that's where
the flame started. And reality check....this is about a
person(s)-to-person(s)
flame. No crews involved...no animosity whatsoever.

3) Posting private email is bad. But I have talked to mike/ow, and it was 
done out of desperation because he didn't understand what was happening. 
>From our perspective, people were joking around and next a serious threat 
surfaced.

4) Old schoolers need to set an example!
Yeah, you motherfuckers on this list! 
Yeah I'm talking to you ;-)
On SFR we are sarcastic bastards, but it has come to my attention that 
our community is read and referenced on-the-outside. "So what?!?" you may 
ask, but the reality is, aside from having light-hearted jabs of 
exchange, what we say impacts how our community is perceived.

I have witnessed us talk shit about candy-ravers, and trance, but...(and I 
don't care what you say)...many of us went through the experience. And 
now, being jaded, doesn't make us any better, or above anyone.

I understand sfr has become a meeting place for us old 
folks, but in our discussion has it ever occurred that our statements are 
offensive? slandering? or at least distancing?

Perhaps not, but I would bet that's how it comes off. And I don't buy the 
argument that it's 'their' problem. It's *our* problem, because the people 
that we are dissing are the very people that will support and define the 
scene that we've committed our lives to thus far. In my opinion the recent 
active old-school scene has done a piss-poor job of embracing the next 
generation. We seem to be really good at criticizing, but not good at 
producing for our future....at all.

5) New-schoolers should understand that old-schoolers are 
self-deprecating and sarcastic.
What I've gathered is that what the old folks consider as playful banter, 
the younger kids view as slander or 'hating' (god I hate that word ;-)

The one thing I've learned in my overall career of throwing parties is to 
not take myself so seriously. I think other older people learned that too. 
In my early days if you talked shit I would have daggers in my eyes. Now I 
could care less about *anything* really, as long as the party was well put 
together, and I worked my tail off in the effort, and everyone had fun!!

6) Old school wants the New school to rock!
The end goal for everyone to thrive and prosper. I get my kicks from 
seeing other people being blown away from what our scene has to offer. I 
like people coming up and asking me what I'm doing tweaking buttons and 
knobs on a pile of gear. Perhaps part of the problem is those of us with 
resources (multiple sound systems, giant lasers, 10 video projectors, 
or just good advice) are not approachable for their efforts.

Ultimately, seeing this recent conflict makes me a bit ill. I hope 
everyone can see the shit-talking for what is is, and snap up, and 
support all positive efforts for our scene.

:-P

-terry

------------------------------------------
terry estioko     | terry@hyperreal.org
SFRaves moderator | http://www.sfraves.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier, Modified, OW.

i agree with ryan, but i also agree with terry and sean.

i've been around for awhile, and know that certain people will
get bent out of shape if you tease them.  sometimes they get
bent over stupid shit, sometimes it's warranted.  personally, i
should have known better than to be poking at this particular
individual.  not a good example from an old(er) listee...again,
my apologies to everyone.

but c'mon:  a playful poke in the ribs does not necessitate a
fist in the face.

in my first post, i was actually defending the "new school"
party, but got punched anyway.  one thing i'm not about are
bullies.  seeing as i grew up getting my ass kicked and then
stuffed in trunks of cars on a weekly basis, i'm not one to
take shit from anyone.

but i temper my posts with humor and sarcasm, a lot of which is
lost on people who don't know me (either online or offline). 
wanna call me a queer?  rock on, thanks!  tell me i'm an old
douche bag?  i'm down.

i took these accusations and name callings with humor, even tho
they were intended (it seems) as insults.  but i agree with
ryan:  don't dish it out if you can't take it.

anyway, i've got more important things to do than to incite
drama that'll end up with a busted party.  had i known that
this was a possibility, i'd have never posted.  i'll just stick
to spamming the list with my BSPs in the future.

nick, no hard feelings.  if i ever meet ya, you can make fun of
my "depends", how much of a fag i am, my crappy DJ abilities,
and how much my music sucks.  no shit.  it's cool.  :)

m

That would be kinda cool to have a basic polyphonic tone generator on
your hip top and a micro composer//sequencer. Someone actually did
that for the GameBoy. Turned the thing into a music composition
instrument. Kinda funny, but not really needed since you can VST's
that emulate that now.

Intead of Mac vs PC how about the future of chip technology and
multicore processors. Now that Intel has given up on the 4GHz chips
they're going to head into the multicore chips like IBM and Motorola
are. Makes a lot more sense to have a dual cpu in one chip using less
power, creating less heat and offering more cpu power than a faster
clocked chip.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ding dong the thread is dead, (empty email)

I just hope that they all start implementing intelligent usage
structures at the processor level, because it's pretty clear that just
about nobody in the software world is taking true multiprocessor
support too seriously right now.

"Uh, we support dual processors- look, the OS goes on one chip (and
takes up 8%) and our app goes on the other!" or "Look, we put all the
really intensive stuff on one processor, and this other side of our app
that really doesn't use any CPU on the other!  That's a 5% increase!!"

Whatever happened to the dream of two processors = ~twice as much
power? ;)

ubergeek gCeee

> that really doesn't use any CPU on the other!  That's a 5% increase!!"
> 
> Whatever happened to the dream of two processors = ~twice as much
> power? ;)
> 
> ubergeek gCeee
> 
> --- innocentchild <innocentchild@gmail.com> wrote:
> > Intead of Mac vs PC how about the future of chip technology and
> > multicore processors. Now that Intel has given up on the 4GHz chips
> > they're going to head into the multicore chips like IBM and Motorola
> > are. Makes a lot more sense to have a dual cpu in one chip using less
> > power, creating less heat and offering more cpu power than a faster
> > clocked chip.
>

Message-ID: <20041223192720.30239.qmail@web51704.mail.yahoo.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Dec 2004 11:27:20 -0800 (PST)
From: matthew johnson <mpj_bay@yahoo.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
In-Reply-To: <47bb6a3004122309186ff813b5@mail.gmail.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier, Modified, OW.

None of this ever happened when everything was
underground. 

Too many parties these days, well since '94. It used
to be everyone went to one party every 6 weeks or so.
Everyone was unified because everyone went to the same
big ass fun underground party. Talked about the same
experience. Not to diss anyone, things are just
different. High school kids didn't go to parties back
then. I was one of the young ones and I was in
college. Hell, the day the scene fell for me was a day
in '94. I walked into a shoe store in the Haight and
heard house music, you never heard electronic music in
public back then... hard to imagine eh?. Next thing I
knew there was a selection of parties to go to every
night. The unity thinned out except for the peeps that
kept it underground. I still go out believe it or not
but on the same terms as WAY back when. Only when
something solid is going on and only every once in a
while. I never got burned out because of this.  

As far as old schoolers go, give us a break. Consider
the fact that if you started going out in the late
80's when the scene REALLY was underground, you
progresses and witnessed the scene going from a tight
family who spread word about parties by a phone tree
and word of mouth, maybe ... maybe black ink hand
bills. Sometimes finding out about a party an hour
before it was ready to go off. People from all over
california and some from OR and WA you would only see
at the parties. Most of these were free or donation as
well because the peeps throwing the party just wanted
peeps to have a good time. Free massages, free water,
etc. Making money wasn't an issue. All the DJ's train
wrecked, even the now big DJ's. Almost every one train
wrecked. DJ's weren't demanding stacks of cash they
were just happy to be part of the party. All of a
sudden big ass color fliers, a party every night of
the week. You started to hear house music or whatever
you want to call it everywhere. Annoying promoters
trying to cash in on the scene. The scene went from
underground to mainstream garbage. Frat boys, high
school kids, I even had to deal with military guys at
one party. Anyone could pick up a flier to any party.
This is not cool. 

So give us old schoolers a break. If you are a new
school kid and like the music, the drugs and the
scene, then learn about what the scene stands for.
Find underground locations. Throw free parties. Throw
parties for the people not the money. Scale back and
bring quality back into the scene. Spread the word by
word of mouth. Unify the people involved. There are
different genres of music these days but if the party
is good and the music of the genre is good then people
will have a good time. Make the drugs cheap again. If
this is your time think really hard why you like the
scene and how you want it to carry on in the future. 

The bay area used to be one of the cornerstones to the
scene in the world. Let's keep it that way and let the
rest of the world hear rumors about parties that are
only heard about.

One last note, I have a recent younger friend who told
me she used to hear about the old school parties back
in the day but didn't believe they actually happened
until I started showing her pictures etc. Now it's
getting time for the new schoolers to carry on the
scene. It's your choice how you go about it and how
you want the future kids to learn about what is
important. Just get it done and do it right. Forget
about how people think of the party and how much money
you can make. Do it to keep the scene alive. See the
big picture.

Enough ranting, peec.

matt
aka dj dub

Rabbit Hunters Shoot Up Ravers

A 46 year old gamekeeper and her female assistant terrorised partygoers 
with shotguns at an illegal all night rave, and pleaded guilty to charges 
of possessing a firearm with intent to cause fear of violence this week, at 
Guildford Crown Court, England.

Reportedly they shot out tyres of ravers' cars, blasted speakers, and 
man-handled the party organisers, after confronting the 600 revellers in a 
dawn showdown.

The woodland party had reportedly been pumping out music since midnight, 
prompting 'scores of complaints from neighbours as far as seven miles 
away'.  The assistant told police they'd been hunting rabbits before 
encountering the ravers, who she said told them to 'fuck off' when the pair 
asked them to leave, prompting their excessive reactions.

Both gun-toting ladies await sentencing.

[skrufff.com]

i've been around for awhile, and know that certain people will
get bent out of shape if you tease them.  sometimes they get
bent over stupid shit, sometimes it's warranted.  personally, i
should have known better than to be poking at this particular
individual.  not a good example from an old(er) listee...again,
my apologies to everyone.

but c'mon:  a playful poke in the ribs does not necessitate a
fist in the face.

in my first post, i was actually defending the "new school"
party, but got punched anyway.  one thing i'm not about are
bullies.  seeing as i grew up getting my ass kicked and then
stuffed in trunks of cars on a weekly basis, i'm not one to
take shit from anyone.

but i temper my posts with humor and sarcasm, a lot of which is
lost on people who don't know me (either online or offline). 
wanna call me a queer?  rock on, thanks!  tell me i'm an old
douche bag?  i'm down.

i took these accusations and name callings with humor, even tho
they were intended (it seems) as insults.  but i agree with
ryan:  don't dish it out if you can't take it.

anyway, i've got more important things to do than to incite
drama that'll end up with a busted party.  had i known that
this was a possibility, i'd have never posted.  i'll just stick
to spamming the list with my BSPs in the future.

nick, no hard feelings.  if i ever meet ya, you can make fun of
my "depends", how much of a fag i am, my crappy DJ abilities,
and how much my music sucks.  no shit.  it's cool.  :)

m

--- matthew johnson <mpj_bay@yahoo.com> wrote:

> None of this ever happened when everything was
> underground. 
> 
> Too many parties these days, well since '94. It used
> to be everyone went to one party every 6 weeks or
> so.
> Everyone was unified because everyone went to the
> same
> big ass fun underground party. Talked about the same
> experience. Not to diss anyone, things are just
> different. High school kids didn't go to parties
> back
> then. I was one of the young ones and I was in
> college. Hell, the day the scene fell for me was a
> day
> in '94. I walked into a shoe store in the Haight and
> heard house music, you never heard electronic music
> in
> public back then... hard to imagine eh?. Next thing
> I
> knew there was a selection of parties to go to every
> night. The unity thinned out except for the peeps
> that
> kept it underground. I still go out believe it or
> not
> but on the same terms as WAY back when. Only when
> something solid is going on and only every once in a
> while. I never got burned out because of this.  
> 
> As far as old schoolers go, give us a break.
> Consider
> the fact that if you started going out in the late
> 80's when the scene REALLY was underground, you
> progresses and witnessed the scene going from a
> tight
> family who spread word about parties by a phone tree
> and word of mouth, maybe ... maybe black ink hand
> bills. Sometimes finding out about a party an hour
> before it was ready to go off. People from all over
> california and some from OR and WA you would only
> see
> at the parties. Most of these were free or donation
> as
> well because the peeps throwing the party just
> wanted
> peeps to have a good time. Free massages, free
> water,
> etc. Making money wasn't an issue. All the DJ's
> train
> wrecked, even the now big DJ's. Almost every one
> train
> wrecked. DJ's weren't demanding stacks of cash they
> were just happy to be part of the party. All of a
> sudden big ass color fliers, a party every night of
> the week. You started to hear house music or
> whatever
> you want to call it everywhere. Annoying promoters
> trying to cash in on the scene. The scene went from
> underground to mainstream garbage. Frat boys, high
> school kids, I even had to deal with military guys
> at
> one party. Anyone could pick up a flier to any
> party.
> This is not cool. 
> 
> So give us old schoolers a break. If you are a new
> school kid and like the music, the drugs and the
> scene, then learn about what the scene stands for.
> Find underground locations. Throw free parties.
> Throw
> parties for the people not the money. Scale back and
> bring quality back into the scene. Spread the word
> by
> word of mouth. Unify the people involved. There are
> different genres of music these days but if the
> party
> is good and the music of the genre is good then
> people
> will have a good time. Make the drugs cheap again.
> If
> this is your time think really hard why you like the
> scene and how you want it to carry on in the future.
> 
> 
> The bay area used to be one of the cornerstones to
> the
> scene in the world. Let's keep it that way and let
> the
> rest of the world hear rumors about parties that are
> only heard about.
> 
> One last note, I have a recent younger friend who
> told
> me she used to hear about the old school parties
> back
> in the day but didn't believe they actually happened
> until I started showing her pictures etc. Now it's
> getting time for the new schoolers to carry on the
> scene. It's your choice how you go about it and how
> you want the future kids to learn about what is
> important. Just get it done and do it right. Forget
> about how people think of the party and how much
> money
> you can make. Do it to keep the scene alive. See the
> big picture.
> 
> Enough ranting, peec.
> 
> matt
> aka dj dub

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The way it should be..

quoth Chris Jackson:
> Get this.  Mind you its London.but why can't WE have a line-up HERE
> like this?

A couple of months ago I probably would have said, "because nobody here
likes techno." But if the fact that the Rickshaw Stop was packed solid
for Swayzak and Matthew Dear on a *Monday* a couple of weeks ago is any
indication, that's just not true.

What the bay area seems to be sorely lacking are promoters with the
right combination of connections, money, and balls to book that kind of
lineup. I spoke briefly to a fellow listmember about the possibility of
a Mutek tour coming to SF, but I haven't heard anything else about it.
And I'm completely in the dark about any decent techno coming up in the
near future aside from on NYE. Anyone?

> I'd be out EVERY weekend if there were shows like this here..

No shit, me too. I'd be down just to see Andrew Weatherall or Robert
Hood by themselves, let alone all those other gods. :)

Speaking of Mr. Weatherall, I have to say the new Two Lone Swordsmen
album is finally growing on me. I didn't really enjoy it the first
couple of times through, but being in a somber mood for a couple of days
straight seems to have made it much more appealing. Those of you into
the electro(clash)/synth-rock thing should definitely check it out.

Toodles,

--- Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:

> I nominate this for the best post to SF-Raves in 2004.
> 
> Regards,
> 
> Peter
> 
> P.S. I put the "old" in Old School ;)
> 
> --- matthew johnson <mpj_bay@yahoo.com> wrote:
> 
> > None of this ever happened when everything was
> > underground. 
> > 
> > Too many parties these days, well since '94. It used
> > to be everyone went to one party every 6 weeks or
> > so.
> > Everyone was unified because everyone went to the
> > same
> > big ass fun underground party. Talked about the same
> > experience. Not to diss anyone, things are just
> > different. High school kids didn't go to parties
> > back
> > then. I was one of the young ones and I was in
> > college. Hell, the day the scene fell for me was a
> > day
> > in '94. I walked into a shoe store in the Haight and
> > heard house music, you never heard electronic music
> > in
> > public back then... hard to imagine eh?. Next thing
> > I
> > knew there was a selection of parties to go to every
> > night. The unity thinned out except for the peeps
> > that
> > kept it underground. I still go out believe it or
> > not
> > but on the same terms as WAY back when. Only when
> > something solid is going on and only every once in a
> > while. I never got burned out because of this.  
> > 
> > As far as old schoolers go, give us a break.
> > Consider
> > the fact that if you started going out in the late
> > 80's when the scene REALLY was underground, you
> > progresses and witnessed the scene going from a
> > tight
> > family who spread word about parties by a phone tree
> > and word of mouth, maybe ... maybe black ink hand
> > bills. Sometimes finding out about a party an hour
> > before it was ready to go off. People from all over
> > california and some from OR and WA you would only
> > see
> > at the parties. Most of these were free or donation
> > as
> > well because the peeps throwing the party just
> > wanted
> > peeps to have a good time. Free massages, free
> > water,
> > etc. Making money wasn't an issue. All the DJ's
> > train
> > wrecked, even the now big DJ's. Almost every one
> > train
> > wrecked. DJ's weren't demanding stacks of cash they
> > were just happy to be part of the party. All of a
> > sudden big ass color fliers, a party every night of
> > the week. You started to hear house music or
> > whatever
> > you want to call it everywhere. Annoying promoters
> > trying to cash in on the scene. The scene went from
> > underground to mainstream garbage. Frat boys, high
> > school kids, I even had to deal with military guys
> > at
> > one party. Anyone could pick up a flier to any
> > party.
> > This is not cool. 
> > 
> > So give us old schoolers a break. If you are a new
> > school kid and like the music, the drugs and the
> > scene, then learn about what the scene stands for.
> > Find underground locations. Throw free parties.
> > Throw
> > parties for the people not the money. Scale back and
> > bring quality back into the scene. Spread the word
> > by
> > word of mouth. Unify the people involved. There are
> > different genres of music these days but if the
> > party
> > is good and the music of the genre is good then
> > people
> > will have a good time. Make the drugs cheap again.
> > If
> > this is your time think really hard why you like the
> > scene and how you want it to carry on in the future.
> > 
> > 
> > The bay area used to be one of the cornerstones to
> > the
> > scene in the world. Let's keep it that way and let
> > the
> > rest of the world hear rumors about parties that are
> > only heard about.
> > 
> > One last note, I have a recent younger friend who
> > told
> > me she used to hear about the old school parties
> > back
> > in the day but didn't believe they actually happened
> > until I started showing her pictures etc. Now it's
> > getting time for the new schoolers to carry on the
> > scene. It's your choice how you go about it and how
> > you want the future kids to learn about what is
> > important. Just get it done and do it right. Forget
> > about how people think of the party and how much
> > money
> > you can make. Do it to keep the scene alive. See the
> > big picture.
> > 
> > Enough ranting, peec.
> > 
> > matt
> > aka dj dub
> >

> > Tired of spam?  Yahoo! Mail has the best spam
> > protection around

At 09:14 PM 12/23/2004, michael, the red stickman wrote:
>i'd agree with you, except for the fact that people didn't go
>out every 6 weeks, we went out every weekend, thursday thru
>sunday.
>
>this is circa '92-95, btw...
>
>m

Sure that.  One could dance non-stop, 24 hours a day, from Friday through 
Monday morning.  This was from the late eighties on here in 
SF.  Amazing,  diverse parties and venues both above and underground.  You 
showed up at an event on Thursday or Friday nite, collected little fliers 
or phone numbers from friends, and you were set for the next 72 hours :-)

Love,

Apollo

of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible

-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

On Thu, 23 Dec 2004 21:24:23 -0800, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
> At 09:14 PM 12/23/2004, michael, the red stickman wrote:
> >i'd agree with you, except for the fact that people didn't go
> >out every 6 weeks, we went out every weekend, thursday thru
> >sunday.
> >
> >this is circa '92-95, btw...
> >
> >m
> 
> Sure that.  One could dance non-stop, 24 hours a day, from Friday through
> Monday morning.  This was from the late eighties on here in
> SF.  Amazing,  diverse parties and venues both above and underground.  You
> showed up at an event on Thursday or Friday nite, collected little fliers
> or phone numbers from friends, and you were set for the next 72 hours :-)
> 
> Love,
> 
> Apollo
> 
> 
> >--- Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:
> >
> > > I nominate this for the best post to SF-Raves in 2004.
> > >
> > > Regards,
> > >
> > > Peter
> > >
> > > P.S. I put the "old" in Old School ;)
> > >
> > > --- matthew johnson <mpj_bay@yahoo.com> wrote:
> > >
> > > > None of this ever happened when everything was
> > > > underground.
> > > >
> > > > Too many parties these days, well since '94. It used
> > > > to be everyone went to one party every 6 weeks or
> > > > so.
> > > > Everyone was unified because everyone went to the
> > > > same
> > > > big ass fun underground party. Talked about the same
> > > > experience. Not to diss anyone, things are just
> > > > different. High school kids didn't go to parties
> > > > back
> > > > then. I was one of the young ones and I was in
> > > > college. Hell, the day the scene fell for me was a
> > > > day
> > > > in '94. I walked into a shoe store in the Haight and
> > > > heard house music, you never heard electronic music
> > > > in
> > > > public back then... hard to imagine eh?. Next thing
> > > > I
> > > > knew there was a selection of parties to go to every
> > > > night. The unity thinned out except for the peeps
> > > > that
> > > > kept it underground. I still go out believe it or
> > > > not
> > > > but on the same terms as WAY back when. Only when
> > > > something solid is going on and only every once in a
> > > > while. I never got burned out because of this.
> > > >
> > > > As far as old schoolers go, give us a break.
> > > > Consider
> > > > the fact that if you started going out in the late
> > > > 80's when the scene REALLY was underground, you
> > > > progresses and witnessed the scene going from a
> > > > tight
> > > > family who spread word about parties by a phone tree
> > > > and word of mouth, maybe ... maybe black ink hand
> > > > bills. Sometimes finding out about a party an hour
> > > > before it was ready to go off. People from all over
> > > > california and some from OR and WA you would only
> > > > see
> > > > at the parties. Most of these were free or donation
> > > > as
> > > > well because the peeps throwing the party just
> > > > wanted
> > > > peeps to have a good time. Free massages, free
> > > > water,
> > > > etc. Making money wasn't an issue. All the DJ's
> > > > train
> > > > wrecked, even the now big DJ's. Almost every one
> > > > train
> > > > wrecked. DJ's weren't demanding stacks of cash they
> > > > were just happy to be part of the party. All of a
> > > > sudden big ass color fliers, a party every night of
> > > > the week. You started to hear house music or
> > > > whatever
> > > > you want to call it everywhere. Annoying promoters
> > > > trying to cash in on the scene. The scene went from
> > > > underground to mainstream garbage. Frat boys, high
> > > > school kids, I even had to deal with military guys
> > > > at
> > > > one party. Anyone could pick up a flier to any
> > > > party.
> > > > This is not cool.
> > > >
> > > > So give us old schoolers a break. If you are a new
> > > > school kid and like the music, the drugs and the
> > > > scene, then learn about what the scene stands for.
> > > > Find underground locations. Throw free parties.
> > > > Throw
> > > > parties for the people not the money. Scale back and
> > > > bring quality back into the scene. Spread the word
> > > > by
> > > > word of mouth. Unify the people involved. There are
> > > > different genres of music these days but if the
> > > > party
> > > > is good and the music of the genre is good then
> > > > people
> > > > will have a good time. Make the drugs cheap again.
> > > > If
> > > > this is your time think really hard why you like the
> > > > scene and how you want it to carry on in the future.
> > > >
> > > >
> > > > The bay area used to be one of the cornerstones to
> > > > the
> > > > scene in the world. Let's keep it that way and let
> > > > the
> > > > rest of the world hear rumors about parties that are
> > > > only heard about.
> > > >
> > > > One last note, I have a recent younger friend who
> > > > told
> > > > me she used to hear about the old school parties
> > > > back
> > > > in the day but didn't believe they actually happened
> > > > until I started showing her pictures etc. Now it's
> > > > getting time for the new schoolers to carry on the
> > > > scene. It's your choice how you go about it and how
> > > > you want the future kids to learn about what is
> > > > important. Just get it done and do it right. Forget
> > > > about how people think of the party and how much
> > > > money
> > > > you can make. Do it to keep the scene alive. See the
> > > > big picture.
> > > >
> > > > Enough ranting, peec.
> > > >
> > > > matt
> > > > aka dj dub
> > > >

At 03:58 PM 12/24/2004, aK wrote:

>so I got some home grown from this co. on eBay. . .

>It seems to effect older cats more than younger ones. . .they eat it, lick 
>it, roll in it, viciously try to get it. . . afterwards they kinda tripp 
>off lil things like noises n objects, and kinda have a lil "whoa" look in 
>their eyes. . .
>
>how does it actually effect them ? The smell seems to effect em, I would 
>guess eating it does too. . . it seems kinda similar to pot. . .
>
>anyone know ? like is it an actual drug effect or are the cats just so 
>attracted to the smell that they just seriously fall in love with the stuff ?

>: )

>aK



The pleasure factor in catnip is the chemical nepetalactone, which seems to 
have a mildly hallucinogenic effect on cats.  Nepetalactone is similar to a 
substance found in the urine of female cats, and this may be why unneutered 
males have stronger reactions to catnip than females and neutered males. 
Some speculate that nepetalactone stimulates the region of a cat's brain 
associated with sexual behavior.

It's not just domestic house cats that have an affinity for catnip -- even 
lions, pumas, and leopards are said to enjoy it. But not every cat will get 
a catnip buzz. Kittens don't react to catnip until they are six to eight 
months old. And roughly 20% to 50% of all cats have no reaction to the 
stuff. Catnip sensitivity is genetic and may also be influenced by learning 
and experience.

Catnip is harmless and non-addictive.

face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

visible."

Christmas and Saturnalia

The early (4th century AD) Church Fathers had no official date to celebrate 
the birth of Jesus.  No one really knows his exact birthday.   The Church, 
however, understood that it was much easier to convert "pagans" to 
Christianity if they adopted the pagan holidays, and often symbology, and 
transformed them into Christian religious events.


Saturnalia

Ancient Romans conveniently happened to have a popular pagan holiday (holy 
day) season called "Saturnalia." Saturnalia, originally celebrated by the 
Romans each year on December the 17th, was a special day set apart for 
honoring the Roman god Saturn. This was a day for nostalgically remembering 
the "Golden Age" of Saturn's beneficent rule. Gifts were exchanged in 
remembrance of the bounty Saturn had once upon a time bestowed upon the 
Roman people.
For the ancient Romans, Saturnalia was joyous celebration of "the good old 
days" when everything had "once-upon-a-time" been right in the world.

In addition to feasting, the Romans celebrated Saturnalia by giving gifts 
of wax candles and earthenware figures, and engaged in temporary role 
reversals. For the celebration, masters would serve their slaves.  A funny 
felt-peaked hat was one costume component.   Decorations included greenery 
swags and garland and gilded objects (gold  to symbolize the yellow sun), 
and candles in window openings.


Rebirth of the Sun

At some point in time, the holy day of Saturnalia had also been tied into 
being a celebration of the rebirth of the Sun - and, as such, Saturnalia 
was held each year about the time of the "winter solstice." Each year, the 
winter solstice marks the beginning of winter. The winter solstice is the 
day each year having the longest night and the shortest amount of sunlight 
hours. After the winter solstice, the daylight hours slowly begin lasting 
longer and longer with each passing day, with this trend of increasing 
sunlight continuing on until the "summer solstice" in June. The summer 
solstice is marked as being the day with longest amount of daylight hours 
and is the official beginning of summer.

The winter solstice takes place each year around December the 21st to mark 
the rebirth of the Sun. In 4th Century AD, the Roman emperor at the time 
"officially" reset Saturnalia to be celebrated on December the 25th (there 
appear to be varying and sometimes contradictory resources regarding 
exactly how and why all this happened).

Shortly thereafter, the Church Fathers likewise set the official date for 
celebrating the birth of Jesus as being December the 25th. What more 
appropriate day could the Church Fathers have "borrowed" for commemorating 
the birth of the Son, than the already extremely popular pagan holiday 
(Saturnalia) set apart for celebrating the rebirth of the true Sun?

Go forth and be merry!!!!

Happy Saturnalia.

Love,

Apollo

bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr. . .how does CatNip work ?

MERRY FESTIVUS EVERYONE!!!!

I'm having the Greatest Festivus....EVER in memory right now, even as
I type this, my life has been one miracle after another, and as Martha
sez, 'it's a good thing.'

great answer Apollo, answered a lot of unasked questions on my end.

I had about a dozen bushes in the garden this year that did so-so,
which I grew for Albert The Benevolent plurtastic kitty that rules our
household with love and wisdom.

He loves him some of that catnip, it's like catnip to him.

We've been buying him a fresh indoor growing plants every week since
the start of the Vernal Equinox from the local farmer's market.

He's usually the most respectful keeper of boundaries that I've ever
seen in a cat, but get him near one of those bad boys and he loses all
of his usual regal sense of deportment.

We've been over the whole 'delayed gratification' bit where if you let
the plants grow todayn there will many more catnip leaves for you
tomorrow, but he obstinately refuses to see it, though today's
Festivus Catnip harvest may finall get him to see the point.

=3DD

n
> > associated with sexual behavior.

> > It's not just domestic house cats that have an affinity for catnip -- e=
ven
> > lions, pumas, and leopards are said to enjoy it. But not every cat will
> get
> > a catnip buzz. Kittens don't react to catnip until they are six to eigh=
t
> > months old. And roughly 20% to 50% of all cats have no reaction to the
> > stuff. Catnip sensitivity is genetic and may also be influenced by
> learning

Subject: [sfraves] NRR - Asia Officials Failed to Issue Warning - Reason for mass death! 20k dead & more expected

Guess we are lucky to live in a place where technology lets up know all that
needs to be known! Even a tacky color scheme to alert us of our current
terror threat level!

Asia Officials Failed to Issue Warnings 


By MICHAEL CASEY, Associated Press Writer 

JAKARTA, Indonesia - Asian officials conceded Monday that they failed to
issue broad public warnings immediately after a massive undersea earthquake
in Indonesia, which could have saved countless lives from the subsequent
giant waves that smashed into nine countries. 


But governments insisted they did not know the true nature of the threat
because there was no international system in place to track tidal waves in
the Indian Ocean - an area where they are rare - and they can't afford to
buy sophisticated equipment to build one. 


And what warnings there were came too little, too late. 


The magnitude 9.0 earthquake - the largest in 40 years - shifted huge
geological plates beneath the sea northwest of Sumatra island, causing a
massive and sudden displacement of millions on tons of water. 


Indonesia villages closest to the temblor's epicenter were swamped within
minutes, but elsewhere the waves radiated outwards, gathering speed and
ferocity until they made landfall. 


Waves began pummeling southern Thailand about one hour after the earthquake.
After 2 1/2 hours, the torrents had traveled some 1,000 miles and slammed
India and Sri Lanka. Malaysia, the Maldives, Myanmar, and Bangladesh were
also hit. Eventually they struck Somalia, on the east coast of Africa. 


The death toll Monday stood at nearly 20,000, with millions left homeless. 


Indonesian officials said they had no way to know that the earthquake had
caused the earthquake-driven waves, or tsunamis, or how dangerous they might
have been. 


"Unfortunately, we have no equipment here that can warn about tsunamis,"
said Budi Waluyo, an official with Indonesia's Meteorology and Geophysics
Agency. "The instruments are very expensive and we don't have money to buy
them." 


But Thammasarote Smith, a former senior forecaster at Thailand's
Meteorological Department, said governments could have done much more to
warn people about the danger. 


"The department had up to an hour to announce the emergency message and
evacuate people but they failed to do so," Thammasarote was quoted as saying
in The Bangkok Post newspaper. "It is true that an earthquake is
unpredictable but a tsunami, which occurs after an earthquake, is
predictable." 


Kathawudhi Marlairojanasiri, the department's chief weather forecaster, said
it had sent out warnings through radio and television from 9 a.m. on Sunday
about a possible undertow along the southwest coast of Thailand, where tens
of thousands of foreign tourists were vacationing. 


But the warnings came after the first waves hit. A Web site warning went up
three hours later - but by then, at least 700 people had died in Thailand,
including a jet-skiing grandson of revered monarch King Bhumibol Adulyadej. 


Sulamee Prachuab, department's Seismological Bureau, said the department
could not give a real-time warning because it did not have the satellite
technology to do it. 


Thai Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra refused to answer reporters'
questions Tuesday about tsunami alerts. 


But Australian Prime Minister John Howard said he would investigate what
role his country could play in setting up an Indian Ocean warning system.
One Australian official said at least a year would be needed to set one up. 


Scientists said seismic networks in the region recorded Sunday's earthquake,
but without wave sensors in oceans that would have tracked the path of the
waves, there was just no way to determine the direction a tsunami would
travel. 

   



"If they had tidal gauges and a tsunami warning system, many people who died
would have been saved," said Waverly Person, director of the U.S. Geological
Survey (news - web sites) national earthquake information service in Golden,
Colo. 

"They could have tracked the waves," he said. "They won't tell you how high
the waves will be, but they can tell you when they will hit. Local
authorities can warn citizens to get off the coast." 

Such a system presumes, however, an organized communication system and
widely understood procedures and discipline by hotel operators, fishing
villages, and local authorities to clear the coastline quickly in case of a
coming disaster. 

Most of developing Asia lacks such infrastructure, and casualties were by
far highest in three highly impoverished areas - the coasts of eastern Sri
Lanka and southeastern India, and the northern tip of Indonesia's Sumatra
island. 

An international warning system in the Pacific was started in 1965, the year
after tsunamis associated with a magnitude 9.2 temblor struck Alaska in
1964. It is administered by the U.S-based National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration. 

Member states include all the major Pacific rim nations in North America,
Asia and South America, as well as the Pacific islands, Australia and New
Zealand. 

Tsunamis occur only occasionally, but they are much rarer in the Indian
Ocean than the Pacific, where one occurs every few years. 

Phil McFadden, chief scientist with the government-funded Geoscience
Australia, said that places close to the epicenter of the earthquake would
have been hit so quickly that any warning would have come too late. 

But if there had been a Pacific-style alert system covering the Indian
Ocean, "there would have been time for people in Sri Lanka, across in the
Maldives or somewhere like that to have done something about it," he said.

Subject: [sfraves]  Fitter Happier, Modified, OW (Back in the Days Thread)

Well I use to go to parties "Back in the days" I started going to parties in 
the early 90's 1991 to be exact. And there are a select few on this list 
that have been going to parties since that time and before so im sure they 
can comment as well.

I disagree that there were very few parties back then. There were a whole 
host of parties back then but it was pretty much all "Underground" back then 
the only difference is that you had the larger parties 
(Gatherings,Basics,Funky tekno tribe,Love american style etc) and you had 
the smaller or mini massive scale (Origin,wally world,wheres waldo etc) and 
I do recall seeing lots of the same people at parties just because I think 
most of us attended quality parties, so therefor you saw alot of the same 
people.

There were alot of promoters back then doing events, but back then I think 
there was more of a network thing going on, for instance if you did a big 
event you didn't dare go against a gathering or basics cause you would most 
likely lose your ass.. So therefore Gathering,FTT and other big crews 
"owned" that night so to speak.. it was more a matter of respect and 
economics.. But that doesn't mean that smaller crews didn't do events on 
that same night like Harmony or other young UG crews of that same era..


Some crews that I recall from early 90's

Martin O'Brien  (Gathering,basics,Vision )
Mike     (Juice parties)
Mark (Where the wild things are)
Vlad Cood (Xmen,FGE)
Jerry and Kevon (Funky Tekno Tribe)
Wally & Jimmy (Sin,Wallly World etc)
Scott & Robbie hardkiss (Oasis nightclub)
Kyle and Lori (Recycle )
Manny from San Jose (Getdown,Getdown,Getdown)
Halim (A rave called Sharon)
Cool world

So those are just 11 promoters that I know from back then. There were a shit 
more but I did not know them personally and don't recall names.

Macadio

>of the week. then there would be one big party every 6
>+/- weeks or so.
>
>btw i love you all .

From: Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
To: "Macadio G." <macadio@hotmail.com>, sfraves@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves]  Fitter Happier, Modified, OW (Back in the Days Thread)

I went to exactly one real party back in the day which
was in late 1993 or 1994.  It was a  full moon party
on the beach at Bonny Doon.  It was a total accident
that I showed up there with some of my hippy Burning
Man friends that my (ex-)wife didn't approve of too
much.  I had no clue what what was going on, but I
caught the vibe.

Later I went to a really weird event, I think it was
called the Freedom Celebration, which was on July 4th
at the Concourse in SF.  It was more of a technology
showcase than a rave which was why I was "on the
list." I was there with my ex-wife and this German
film crew that was documenting my family at the time
(it was called *Cyberland* and its in German if you
can find a copy.) Timothy Leary and all the Mondo 2000
folks where there.  The stereoscopic projections were
awesome, but the party, well it sucked.

I went to one quasi-rave in Orlando in the summer of
1994 that was totally crazy with people dancing on the
speakers and everything.  We were at SIGGRAPH and
totally sleep deprived so maybe I imagined the whole
thing.

Since I remarried I started going out again, but more
to clubs than undergrounds because, well its reliable
and I know some of the DJs etc.  Hey I'm old and out
of the loop. ;)

Peace,

Peter

> most of us attended quality parties, so therefor you
> saw alot of the same 
> people.
> 
> There were alot of promoters back then doing events,
> but back then I think 
> there was more of a network thing going on, for
> instance if you did a big 
> event you didn't dare go against a gathering or
> basics cause you would most 
> likely lose your ass.. So therefore Gathering,FTT
> and other big crews 
> "owned" that night so to speak.. it was more a
> matter of respect and 
> economics.. But that doesn't mean that smaller crews
> didn't do events on 
> that same night like Harmony or other young UG crews
> of that same era..
> 
> 
> Some crews that I recall from early 90's
> 
> Martin O'Brien  (Gathering,basics,Vision )
> Mike     (Juice parties)
> Mark (Where the wild things are)
> Vlad Cood (Xmen,FGE)
> Jerry and Kevon (Funky Tekno Tribe)
> Wally & Jimmy (Sin,Wallly World etc)
> Scott & Robbie hardkiss (Oasis nightclub)
> Kyle and Lori (Recycle )
> Manny from San Jose (Getdown,Getdown,Getdown)
> Halim (A rave called Sharon)
> Cool world
> 
> So those are just 11 promoters that I know from back
> then. There were a shit 
> more but I did not know them personally and don't
> recall names.
> 
> Macadio
> 
> 
> >From: matthew johnson <mpj_bay@yahoo.com>
> >To: sfraves@hyperreal.org

--- "Macadio G." <macadio@hotmail.com> wrote:

> Well I use to go to parties "Back in the days" I
> started going to parties in 
> the early 90's 1991 to be exact. And there are a
> select few on this list 
> that have been going to parties since that time and
> before so im sure they 
> can comment as well.
> 
> I disagree that there were very few parties back
> then. There were a whole 
> host of parties back then but it was pretty much all
> "Underground" back then 
> the only difference is that you had the larger
> parties 
> (Gatherings,Basics,Funky tekno tribe,Love american
> style etc) and you had 
> the smaller or mini massive scale (Origin,wally
> world,wheres waldo etc) and 
> I do recall seeing lots of the same people at
> parties just because I think 
> most of us attended quality parties, so therefor you
> saw alot of the same 
> people.
> 
> There were alot of promoters back then doing events,
> but back then I think 
> there was more of a network thing going on, for
> instance if you did a big 
> event you didn't dare go against a gathering or
> basics cause you would most 
> likely lose your ass.. So therefore Gathering,FTT
> and other big crews 
> "owned" that night so to speak.. it was more a
> matter of respect and 
> economics.. But that doesn't mean that smaller crews
> didn't do events on 
> that same night like Harmony or other young UG crews
> of that same era..
> 
> 
> Some crews that I recall from early 90's
> 
> Martin O'Brien  (Gathering,basics,Vision )
> Mike     (Juice parties)
> Mark (Where the wild things are)
> Vlad Cood (Xmen,FGE)
> Jerry and Kevon (Funky Tekno Tribe)
> Wally & Jimmy (Sin,Wallly World etc)
> Scott & Robbie hardkiss (Oasis nightclub)
> Kyle and Lori (Recycle )
> Manny from San Jose (Getdown,Getdown,Getdown)
> Halim (A rave called Sharon)
> Cool world
> 
> So those are just 11 promoters that I know from back
> then. There were a shit 
> more but I did not know them personally and don't
> recall names.
> 
> Macadio
> 
> 
> >From: matthew johnson <mpj_bay@yahoo.com>
> >To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> >Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: Fitter Happier,
> Modified, OW.

> had
> >back then. 90- early 93, late 93, 94 started
> getting
> >crazy. now you have many parties to chose from any
> day
> >of the week. then there would be one big party
> every 6
> >+/- weeks or so.

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

MICHAEL GARRETT
1952-2004

Michael Garrett, longtime admired DJ and owner of the CD Record Rack, who 
achieved fame playing at the I-Beam, Trocadero, Galleria and Giftcenter 
parties, passed away at home in his sleep on December 10, 2004. He is 
survived by three brothers, Tim in San Francisco, Richard and Phillip in 
Texas, partner Robert Kimler, longtime close friend Steve Fabus, Randy 
Schiller, Sam Schneider, Jerry Bonham, Jimmy Horde and many other friends, 
associates and admirers.

Michael was a showman that reminded DJ's that "making a musical statement 
is great as long as you're giving people a party". Michael loved San 
Francisco and in many ways personified the city with his charm, wit and 
playful irreverence. He made you feel at home and part of a family on and 
off his dance floor. His long running Sunday T-Dance at the I-Beam gave 
people a sense of connection and belonging throughout the darkest days of 
the epidemic, and his record store, the CD Record Rack was a social center 
for the community.

Michael would be the first to remind you that life should be pleasurable. 
That we are here to break down barriers and explore. To live life to the 
fullest. Not to take ourselves too seriously. And definately have some fun.

A gathering of friends will celebrate Michael's time in their lives on 
Saturday, January 15, 2005 at 2pm at Moby Dick, 4089 18th Street in the 
Castro. Please contact Steve Fabus at sfabus@sbcglobal.net for more 
information.




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm


"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"



--=====================_13394570==.ALT--

Subject: [sfraves] Finally, a clean way to block ads? (and NYE)

Randomly stumbled upon this just a few minutes ago and thought it was so
clean that I should share it with you.  Firefox appears to really
cleanly block ads.  They document some CSS that you can use here:
http://www.mozilla.org/support/firefox/adblock
The file they refer to doesn't exist by default, and you likely will
have to click through a link or 2 to figure out exactly where the file
should reside on your OS, but it's well worth it.

Once you're done, check out the difference at my site
(http://www.jcthedj.com) for example, both in Firefox with adblocking
and in another browser without adblocking.  Firefox CLEANLY blocks the
ad!  I'm impressed!

So, to keep this RR, who's going where for NYE?

http://www.jcthedj.com
AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

to goth, industrial, and more poppy shit like new order,
depeche mode, and book of love.  he was one of the first people
to introduce me to acid house.

terrible news.

michael: you shall be missed, old friend.
